1
00:00:44,440 --> 00:00:46,340
CHAPTER ONE
The Future

2
00:00:46,340 --> 00:00:50,140
Friday, 15th July 1988

3
00:00:50,140 --> 00:00:53,930
Rankeillor Street, Edinburgh, Scotland

4
00:00:53,930 --> 00:01:03,500
'The important thing in life is to make a
difference - to make a change to something,'

5
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:05,309
the girl said.

6
00:01:05,309 --> 00:01:09,100
'Ah - you mean we have to change the world?'

7
00:01:09,100 --> 00:01:10,540
the boy replied.

8
00:01:10,540 --> 00:01:18,360
'No, not all of the world, we just have to
change the bit of it around us,' the girl

9
00:01:18,360 --> 00:01:19,360
said.

10
00:01:19,360 --> 00:01:22,750
She was silent for a moment, then she laughed
at herself.

11
00:01:22,750 --> 00:01:24,810
'I can't believe I said that.

12
00:01:24,810 --> 00:01:28,530
It's such a predictable thing to say, isn't
it?

13
00:01:28,530 --> 00:01:32,390
But what are you going to do with your life?

14
00:01:32,390 --> 00:01:33,740
What's your plan?'

15
00:01:33,740 --> 00:01:38,630
'Well, my parents are coming to collect me
later today,' he told her.

16
00:01:38,630 --> 00:01:44,170
'Then I'll go to France for a few weeks and
after that, maybe I'll go to China.'

17
00:01:44,170 --> 00:01:48,550
'Oh, you're going travelling,' she said wearily.

18
00:01:48,550 --> 00:01:50,569
'You're predictable too.

19
00:01:50,569 --> 00:01:54,289
You've got too much money, that's your problem,
Dexter.

20
00:01:54,289 --> 00:01:59,630
What you really mean is that you're running
away from real life.'

21
00:01:59,630 --> 00:02:03,850
'Travelling broadens the mind, Emma,' he said
slowly.

22
00:02:03,850 --> 00:02:07,050
He was trying to copy the girl's accent.

23
00:02:07,050 --> 00:02:10,340
Suddenly, he leaned over her and kissed her.

24
00:02:10,340 --> 00:02:16,750
'I think you're too broad-minded now,' the
girl said, quickly turning her face away from

25
00:02:16,750 --> 00:02:18,230
him.

26
00:02:18,230 --> 00:02:21,690
The girl was from Yorkshire, in the north
of England.

27
00:02:21,690 --> 00:02:28,130
She was used to posh boys from the south making
fun of her soft northern accent.

28
00:02:28,130 --> 00:02:33,470
Sometimes she didn't care, but now she suddenly
felt annoyed with the boy.

29
00:02:33,470 --> 00:02:35,420
Everything was going wrong tonight.

30
00:02:35,420 --> 00:02:41,440
'Anyway, I'm not talking about the immediate
future,' she told him.

31
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:48,909
'I'm not asking about tomorrow, I'm asking
what you want to be in twenty years from now.'

32
00:02:48,909 --> 00:02:53,460
At first, the best answer he could think of
was 'I want to be rich and famous'.

33
00:02:53,460 --> 00:02:57,460
But then he thought a bit more and spoke seriously.

34
00:02:57,460 --> 00:03:02,070
'I don't ever want to be different from this,'
he said.

35
00:03:02,070 --> 00:03:05,580
'I'd like to stay exactly as I am now.

36
00:03:05,580 --> 00:03:11,370
Every fifteenth of July, I want to be just
like this.'

37
00:03:11,370 --> 00:03:13,560
The girl was called Emma Morley.

38
00:03:13,560 --> 00:03:16,260
The boy's name was Dexter Mayhew.

39
00:03:16,260 --> 00:03:20,780
They were lying on the narrow bed in Emma's
room in a shared flat.

40
00:03:20,780 --> 00:03:23,350
It was four o'clock in the morning.

41
00:03:23,350 --> 00:03:28,400
The two young people didn't know each other
very well, but certainly this was a night

42
00:03:28,400 --> 00:03:30,030
for thinking about the future.

43
00:03:30,030 --> 00:03:34,170
It was the last night of their university
life in Edinburgh.

44
00:03:34,170 --> 00:03:39,040
Earlier in the day, after four years, they
had finally graduated.

45
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:43,650
Soon they would go in separate directions.

46
00:03:43,650 --> 00:03:46,939
Emma looked up at the boy as he leaned over
her.

47
00:03:46,939 --> 00:03:52,430
She was a little annoyed with him, but she
still thought that he was handsome.

48
00:03:52,430 --> 00:03:54,730
'Mm - handsome.

49
00:03:54,730 --> 00:03:57,890
Perhaps "beautiful" is a better word,' she
thought.

50
00:03:57,890 --> 00:04:05,140
And she knew that lots of the other girl students
agreed with her - especially the posh ones

51
00:04:05,140 --> 00:04:06,580
from the south.

52
00:04:06,580 --> 00:04:11,640
They all knew that he would get their clothes
off and get them into his bed.

53
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:17,269
His body was muscular and the skin of his
face was tight.

54
00:04:17,269 --> 00:04:19,980
His eyebrows were slim and his lips were full.

55
00:04:19,980 --> 00:04:27,260
'Yes, he's beautiful, but he looks a little
like a cat,' Emma told herself.

56
00:04:27,260 --> 00:04:33,630
'I think I can imagine you when you're forty,'
she said unkindly.

57
00:04:33,630 --> 00:04:39,690
'You'll have an expensive red sports car and
live in the most expensive part of London.

58
00:04:39,690 --> 00:04:44,800
You'll be married to your third wife - no,
I'm wrong, your fourth wife.

59
00:04:44,800 --> 00:04:46,700
There won't be any children.

60
00:04:46,700 --> 00:04:50,200
You're too selfish for children.

61
00:04:50,200 --> 00:04:54,400
No children, just three expensive divorces.'

62
00:04:54,400 --> 00:04:57,900
'Well, Em,' Dexter began crossly.

63
00:04:57,900 --> 00:04:59,300
'Who's "Em"?'

64
00:04:59,300 --> 00:05:00,940
Emma quickly asked.

65
00:05:00,940 --> 00:05:06,290
'Your friends call you "Em", I've heard them
call you that,' he said.

66
00:05:06,290 --> 00:05:11,530
'Ah, yes, my friends call me that,' Emma replied.

67
00:05:11,530 --> 00:05:15,400
'Can't I call you that?' he asked.

68
00:05:15,400 --> 00:05:16,930
He sounded worried.

69
00:05:16,930 --> 00:05:20,600
'Oh, all right then, Dex,' she said.

70
00:05:20,600 --> 00:05:21,670
'Go on.'

71
00:05:21,670 --> 00:05:27,639
'Well, if you think I'm so terrible why are
you sleeping with me?' he asked.

72
00:05:27,639 --> 00:05:34,630
'Well, I don't think I really have slept with
you, have I?' she replied.

73
00:05:34,630 --> 00:05:41,170
'You can choose either meaning of "sleep"
- I mean, we haven't been to sleep and we

74
00:05:41,170 --> 00:05:43,750
haven't done anything else, have we?'

75
00:05:43,750 --> 00:05:50,130
'No,' the boy said, 'no, we haven't quite
done that.'

76
00:05:50,130 --> 00:05:53,330
Tonight Emma had wanted something different.

77
00:05:53,330 --> 00:05:58,030
She wasn't sure what it was, but their names
sounded good together.

78
00:05:58,030 --> 00:06:01,650
'Emma and Dexter,' she thought.

79
00:06:01,650 --> 00:06:03,530
'Em and Dex.'

80
00:06:03,530 --> 00:06:06,669
'Wait there,' Emma said.

81
00:06:06,669 --> 00:06:09,600
'I'm just going to the bathroom.

82
00:06:09,600 --> 00:06:11,220
Don't go away.'

83
00:06:11,220 --> 00:06:16,200
She put on her thick glasses and walked towards
the door.

84
00:06:16,200 --> 00:06:20,889
In the bathroom, Emma asked herself why she
was being difficult with the boy.

85
00:06:20,889 --> 00:06:28,480
'He's certainly very bourgeois and he isn't
very clever, but I really like him,' she told

86
00:06:28,480 --> 00:06:30,340
herself.

87
00:06:30,340 --> 00:06:35,520
Emma had liked Dexter since she'd first met
him at a party two years before.

88
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:40,130
But she'd never got to know him and in just
a few hours he would be gone.

89
00:06:40,130 --> 00:06:44,680
And he certainly wasn't going to ask her to
go to China with him.

90
00:06:44,680 --> 00:06:46,470
It was a bit sad.

91
00:06:46,470 --> 00:06:51,440
For the first time in four years she was with
a boy she really liked.

92
00:06:51,440 --> 00:06:54,270
But she couldn't relax with him.

93
00:06:54,270 --> 00:06:59,650
They had been kissing and talking for eight
hours now and she still didn't know what she

94
00:06:59,650 --> 00:07:01,090
wanted.

95
00:07:01,090 --> 00:07:05,260
Dexter, waiting in the bedroom, looked around
him.

96
00:07:05,260 --> 00:07:11,740
He had been in so many rooms like this one
- rooms where girls like Emma lived.

97
00:07:11,740 --> 00:07:17,729
These girls always wore t-shirts with political
slogans on the fronts.

98
00:07:17,729 --> 00:07:21,210
There were always political posters on their
walls.

99
00:07:21,210 --> 00:07:24,770
There were always CDs of political songs.

100
00:07:24,770 --> 00:07:29,570
They were all the same, these girls with socialist
ideas.

101
00:07:29,570 --> 00:07:35,889
They always thought that he was horribly bourgeois
and they always thought that being bourgeois

102
00:07:35,889 --> 00:07:37,050
was bad.

103
00:07:37,050 --> 00:07:40,280
Well, he had news for them.

104
00:07:40,280 --> 00:07:45,360
He thought that being bourgeois was just fine.

105
00:07:45,360 --> 00:07:47,770
Dexter hadn't really decided yet on a map
for his future life.

106
00:07:47,770 --> 00:07:54,550
But he was twenty-three years old and he had
some ambitions.

107
00:07:54,550 --> 00:08:00,600
He wanted to be successful at something - he
just didn't know at what.

108
00:08:00,600 --> 00:08:04,140
He wanted to make his parents proud of him.

109
00:08:04,140 --> 00:08:06,770
He wanted to meet lots of women.

110
00:08:06,770 --> 00:08:12,570
He wanted to have lots of fun in his life
and he wanted never to be sad.

111
00:08:12,570 --> 00:08:19,039
Thinking about fun and sadness, Dexter was
now feeling that this night had been a mistake.

112
00:08:19,039 --> 00:08:20,720
There were going to be tears.

113
00:08:20,720 --> 00:08:25,289
There were going to be angry phone calls.

114
00:08:25,289 --> 00:08:28,250
Emma returned and lay down beside him again.

115
00:08:28,250 --> 00:08:32,250
She had put on a t-shirt with a political
slogan on the front.

116
00:08:32,250 --> 00:08:36,399
'Do you mind if we just cuddle, Dex?'

117
00:08:36,399 --> 00:08:37,940
Emma said.

118
00:08:37,940 --> 00:08:42,479
Dexter didn't think this was a good idea at
all, but he didn't say so.

119
00:08:42,479 --> 00:08:47,649
'OK, if that's what you want,' he said, without
interest.

120
00:08:47,649 --> 00:08:54,310
'I can't believe I just said "cuddle",' Emma
said, after a minute of silence.

121
00:08:54,310 --> 00:08:58,310
'What a terrible bourgeois word for me to
use!

122
00:08:58,310 --> 00:08:59,310
I'm sorry.'

123
00:08:59,310 --> 00:09:02,420
'We must get some sleep,' said Dexter.

124
00:09:02,420 --> 00:09:06,130
He was thinking, 'This must never happen again.'

125
00:09:06,130 --> 00:09:10,290
There was daylight outside the window.

126
00:09:10,290 --> 00:09:14,990
Dexter was still awake and he was looking
at Emma, who was sleeping next to him.

127
00:09:14,990 --> 00:09:20,140
'I could leave quietly now, before she wakes
up,' he told himself.

128
00:09:20,140 --> 00:09:23,230
'Then I don't need to see her again.

129
00:09:23,230 --> 00:09:25,010
Will she mind?

130
00:09:25,010 --> 00:09:28,380
Probably, girls usually do mind.

131
00:09:28,380 --> 00:09:30,800
But will I mind?'

132
00:09:30,800 --> 00:09:34,870
It was strange, but the answer to this was
not clear to Dexter.

133
00:09:34,870 --> 00:09:38,180
There was something about Emma.

134
00:09:38,180 --> 00:09:41,980
She was pretty, but she seemed to hate herself
for that.

135
00:09:41,980 --> 00:09:46,630
The red colour of her hair was out of a bottle
and her hairstyle was awful.

136
00:09:46,630 --> 00:09:52,940
Dexter guessed that Emma's hair had been cut
by Tilly Killick, the large, noisy girl who

137
00:09:52,940 --> 00:09:56,110
lived in the other room in this flat.

138
00:09:56,110 --> 00:09:59,240
'But never mind the hair,' Dexter thought.

139
00:09:59,240 --> 00:10:04,690
'Her face is really pretty and her body's
amazing.'

140
00:10:04,690 --> 00:10:11,220
Soon he decided that he would leave quietly,
never mind what Emma's face and body were

141
00:10:11,220 --> 00:10:12,220
like.

142
00:10:12,220 --> 00:10:16,150
'I'll probably never see her again,' he told
himself.

143
00:10:16,150 --> 00:10:20,260
Dexter was about to get quietly out of bed
when Emma woke up.

144
00:10:20,260 --> 00:10:23,880
'What are you doing later today?'

145
00:10:23,880 --> 00:10:25,580
she asked, sleepily.

146
00:10:25,580 --> 00:10:29,880
'Tell her you're busy!' said a voice in Dexter's
head.

147
00:10:29,880 --> 00:10:34,350
'I don't have any plans,' he said aloud.

148
00:10:34,350 --> 00:10:37,880
'Shall we do something together then?'

149
00:10:37,880 --> 00:10:39,060
she asked.

150
00:10:39,060 --> 00:10:42,420
'Yes, all right,' Dexter said.

151
00:10:42,420 --> 00:10:59,890
A moment later, Emma was asleep again.

152
00:10:59,890 --> 00:11:01,760
CHAPTER TWO
Real Life

153
00:11:01,760 --> 00:11:07,690
Saturday, 15th July 1989

154
00:11:07,690 --> 00:11:13,540
Wolverhampton, England and Rome, Italy

155
00:11:13,540 --> 00:11:16,410
Emma Morley was writing a letter.

156
00:11:16,410 --> 00:11:19,600
Stoke Park School, Wolverhampton

157
00:11:19,600 --> 00:11:21,200
Hello Dexter,

158
00:11:21,200 --> 00:11:22,200
How are you?

159
00:11:22,200 --> 00:11:24,040
How is Rome?

160
00:11:24,040 --> 00:11:27,120
How is La Dolce Vita?

161
00:11:27,120 --> 00:11:29,440
(Try a dictionary!)

162
00:11:29,440 --> 00:11:35,380
I know that some people call Rome 'the eternal
city' but I've been here in Wolverhampton

163
00:11:35,380 --> 00:11:39,580
for two days now and they have felt eternal
to me.

164
00:11:39,580 --> 00:11:43,350
So perhaps Wolverhampton should be called
by that name.

165
00:11:43,350 --> 00:11:44,580
Ha ha.

166
00:11:44,580 --> 00:11:50,320
Well, I decided to take the job I told you
about, so I'm working with Sledgehammer Theatre.

167
00:11:50,320 --> 00:11:52,269
It's a Theatre-in-Education group.

168
00:11:52,269 --> 00:11:58,610
For the past month, we've been touring schools
with a play about slavery.

169
00:11:58,610 --> 00:12:02,510
Today we're performing it at this fine school.

170
00:12:02,510 --> 00:12:08,450
Anyway, we try to show 11-13-year olds that
slavery was A BAD THING.

171
00:12:08,450 --> 00:12:11,730
Aren't we brave and original!

172
00:12:11,730 --> 00:12:15,390
Really, I don't know why I am being nasty
about my job.

173
00:12:15,390 --> 00:12:21,240
A lot of the kids have never thought about
social problems of the past until now.

174
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:28,200
And now some of them - the ones that don't
throw things at us - are becoming really interested.

175
00:12:28,200 --> 00:12:33,350
So I still think that we can make a difference
for people.

176
00:12:33,350 --> 00:12:35,770
Emma was trying to be positive.

177
00:12:35,770 --> 00:12:38,750
She had to try hard.

178
00:12:38,750 --> 00:12:41,670
The last year had been full of mistakes.

179
00:12:41,670 --> 00:12:46,340
After her graduation, she had stayed on in
Edinburgh.

180
00:12:46,340 --> 00:12:50,180
But she had made a series of bad career choices.

181
00:12:50,180 --> 00:12:55,420
There was the terrible all-girl band she had
played in.

182
00:12:55,420 --> 00:12:59,860
There was her first novel, which she had stopped
writing.

183
00:12:59,860 --> 00:13:05,790
There was her second novel, which she had
also stopped writing.

184
00:13:05,790 --> 00:13:09,010
She had worked in shops, trying to sell things
to tourists.

185
00:13:09,010 --> 00:13:14,279
But the tourists never really wanted the things
she tried to sell them.

186
00:13:14,279 --> 00:13:19,770
So finally she had moved back to Yorkshire
to live with her parents.

187
00:13:19,770 --> 00:13:22,540
That wasn't good either.

188
00:13:22,540 --> 00:13:27,310
'But you've got a really good degree,' Emma's
mother said almost daily.

189
00:13:27,310 --> 00:13:32,820
'Why on earth don't you use it to get yourself
a good job?'

190
00:13:32,820 --> 00:13:37,880
From time to time, Dexter Mayhew became part
of her life for a few days.

191
00:13:37,880 --> 00:13:43,170
At the end of the summer, she had gone to
stay at his rich parents' huge house in the

192
00:13:43,170 --> 00:13:44,170
countryside.

193
00:13:44,170 --> 00:13:48,110
But that had gone terribly wrong.

194
00:13:48,110 --> 00:13:53,420
Emma had had too much to drink one evening
and had argued with Dexter's father about

195
00:13:53,420 --> 00:13:55,300
politics.

196
00:13:55,300 --> 00:13:59,589
She had shouted at him and told him he was
a bourgeois fascist.

197
00:13:59,589 --> 00:14:05,850
Then, more recently, they had met up in London
for the birthday party of one of their friends

198
00:14:05,850 --> 00:14:09,340
- a man called Callum O'Neill.

199
00:14:09,340 --> 00:14:12,990
Callum had shared a flat with Dexter in Edinburgh.

200
00:14:12,990 --> 00:14:18,260
He now had a successful business selling computers.

201
00:14:18,260 --> 00:14:21,980
Dexter and Emma had spent the day after the
party together.

202
00:14:21,980 --> 00:14:27,029
Most of the day they lay on the grass in Kensington
Gardens.

203
00:14:27,029 --> 00:14:30,350
They drank wine from a bottle and they talked.

204
00:14:30,350 --> 00:14:37,010
They never quite touched each other and Dexter
told her all about a wonderful Spanish girl

205
00:14:37,010 --> 00:14:38,690
called Lola.

206
00:14:38,690 --> 00:14:43,070
Emma decided that this was all their friendship
was ever going to be.

207
00:14:43,070 --> 00:14:46,660
Clearly, Dexter didn't want to sleep with
her.

208
00:14:46,660 --> 00:14:49,829
He wanted to tell her about the other girls
he slept with.

209
00:14:49,829 --> 00:14:57,170
But strangely, Dexter also told her that his
mother had liked her very much.

210
00:14:57,170 --> 00:15:02,430
'She says she has a good feeling about you
and me,' he'd said.

211
00:15:02,430 --> 00:15:08,100
At the time, Emma hadn't understood the importance
of Dexter's words.

212
00:15:08,100 --> 00:15:13,330
Emma didn't know that Dexter loved his mother
more than anyone in the world.

213
00:15:13,330 --> 00:15:17,110
And she didn't know that Dexter's mother felt
the same about him.

214
00:15:17,110 --> 00:15:21,220
Then Dexter had gone travelling again.

215
00:15:21,220 --> 00:15:24,700
When he was away, Emma wrote him long letters.

216
00:15:24,700 --> 00:15:26,460
He usually replied on postcards.

217
00:15:26,460 --> 00:15:31,700
'We're just pen pals now,' Emma told herself.

218
00:15:31,700 --> 00:15:35,040
'We'll never be anything more to each other.'

219
00:15:35,040 --> 00:15:42,390
Emma got a job in a pub for a while, but living
with her parents was killing her mind.

220
00:15:42,390 --> 00:15:47,240
When an old friend phoned and offered her
a job in his theatre group, she'd accepted

221
00:15:47,240 --> 00:15:48,240
it immediately.

222
00:15:48,240 --> 00:15:52,889
But now, after three months, Emma hated the
theatre group.

223
00:15:52,889 --> 00:15:57,329
'I don't want to be here making a difference,'
she thought.

224
00:15:57,329 --> 00:15:59,820
'I want to be in Rome.

225
00:15:59,820 --> 00:16:02,040
I want to be with Dexter Mayhew.'

226
00:16:02,040 --> 00:16:05,970
Emma made herself continue with her letter.

227
00:16:05,970 --> 00:16:09,350
Anyway, I've got a new plan.

228
00:16:09,350 --> 00:16:14,560
I've written a two-woman play about Virginia
Woolf and Emily Dickinson.

229
00:16:14,560 --> 00:16:19,970
One of my friends from the theatre group and
I want to find somewhere in London where we

230
00:16:19,970 --> 00:16:21,399
can stage it.

231
00:16:21,399 --> 00:16:24,790
Do you remember my friend Tilly Killick?

232
00:16:24,790 --> 00:16:27,920
We shared a flat in Edinburgh.

233
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:31,430
She lives in London now and she has a spare
room in her flat.

234
00:16:31,430 --> 00:16:35,269
So I'll probably live there for a few months.

235
00:16:35,269 --> 00:16:37,600
Are you coming back to London soon?

236
00:16:37,600 --> 00:16:41,639
Maybe we could be flat mates?

237
00:16:41,639 --> 00:16:43,190
Emma stopped writing.

238
00:16:43,190 --> 00:16:45,550
Suddenly she felt nervous.

239
00:16:45,550 --> 00:16:49,560
Then she wrote: It's all right, I'm just joking!

240
00:16:49,560 --> 00:16:53,700
But I really miss you, Dex.

241
00:16:53,700 --> 00:16:56,829
And she signed her name.

242
00:16:56,829 --> 00:16:59,420
In Rome, Dexter was out with a Danish girl.

243
00:16:59,420 --> 00:17:04,339
He was working as an English teacher and the
girl was one of his students.

244
00:17:04,339 --> 00:17:06,040
She was nineteen.

245
00:17:06,040 --> 00:17:10,240
'I have an exam on Monday,' the girl said.

246
00:17:10,240 --> 00:17:13,839
'Test me on verbs, please, Dexter.'

247
00:17:13,839 --> 00:17:19,010
'All right - the present continuous,' Dexter
replied.

248
00:17:19,010 --> 00:17:26,709
'I am kissing, you are kissing, he is kissing...'
said the girl.

249
00:17:26,709 --> 00:17:28,799
She showed him how to kiss too.

250
00:17:28,799 --> 00:17:36,500
'But what would Emma Morley think about this?'

251
00:17:36,500 --> 00:17:48,539
Dexter suddenly thought.

252
00:17:48,539 --> 00:17:50,700
CHAPTER THREE
The Taj Mahal

253
00:17:50,700 --> 00:17:55,899
Sunday, 15th July 1990

254
00:17:55,899 --> 00:18:03,549
Camden Town, London and Bombay, India

255
00:18:03,549 --> 00:18:10,729
'The restaurant opens in ten minutes and I
have a few things to tell you.'

256
00:18:10,729 --> 00:18:19,110
Scott was the manager of Loco Caliente, a
Tex-Mex restaurant in Camden Town, North London.

257
00:18:19,110 --> 00:18:21,769
The restaurant was one of a chain.

258
00:18:21,769 --> 00:18:27,809
'First, these are the special dishes for this
lunchtime,' Scott went on when his staff had

259
00:18:27,809 --> 00:18:29,019
stopped talking.

260
00:18:29,019 --> 00:18:32,260
'Today's special soup is corn chowder.'

261
00:18:32,260 --> 00:18:39,169
Several of the waiters pretended to be sick
and he stopped talking again for a few seconds.

262
00:18:39,169 --> 00:18:47,570
'And today's other special dish is "an amazing
fish burrito" which contains "delicious pieces

263
00:18:47,570 --> 00:18:49,899
of cod and prawns".

264
00:18:49,899 --> 00:18:55,519
That's how the document from headquarters
describes it, anyway - and those are the words

265
00:18:55,519 --> 00:18:58,720
you must use too.'

266
00:18:58,720 --> 00:19:03,039
'It sounds really horrible,' said one of the
waiters, laughing.

267
00:19:03,039 --> 00:19:09,700
'Look at it this way - we're bringing a taste
of the North Atlantic to the beaches of Mexico,'

268
00:19:09,700 --> 00:19:12,109
said Emma Morley.

269
00:19:12,109 --> 00:19:15,399
She sounded very tired as she made the joke.

270
00:19:15,399 --> 00:19:21,159
As she tied her waitress's apron round her
waist she noticed someone she hadn't seen

271
00:19:21,159 --> 00:19:25,129
before - a large man with curly, blonde hair.

272
00:19:25,129 --> 00:19:28,090
He was wearing a waiter's uniform and he was
quite nice-looking.

273
00:19:28,090 --> 00:19:34,350
'And now here's some good news at last,' said
Scott.

274
00:19:34,350 --> 00:19:36,179
He pointed at the stranger.

275
00:19:36,179 --> 00:19:40,859
'This is Ian Whitehead, who is joining our
happy team.

276
00:19:40,859 --> 00:19:43,659
Ian - this is Emma.

277
00:19:43,659 --> 00:19:44,889
She'll look after you today.

278
00:19:44,889 --> 00:19:48,729
She's been here longer than all the others.'

279
00:19:48,729 --> 00:19:51,870
Emma did not think that this was anything
to be proud of.

280
00:19:51,870 --> 00:19:59,159
She gave Ian a little smile as one of the
waiters turned on the lunchtime music.

281
00:19:59,159 --> 00:20:03,580
The first song was, of course, 'La Cucaracha'.

282
00:20:03,580 --> 00:20:07,440
She asked herself once more what she was doing
here.

283
00:20:07,440 --> 00:20:12,039
She asked herself once more what she was going
to do with her life.

284
00:20:12,039 --> 00:20:18,159
Later, when Emma was showing Ian what he should
do, she asked him about himself.

285
00:20:18,159 --> 00:20:20,979
'I need to be in London,' he said.

286
00:20:20,979 --> 00:20:25,489
'I took this job because I need to earn some
money on the side.'

287
00:20:25,489 --> 00:20:26,489
'Why?

288
00:20:26,489 --> 00:20:29,509
What do you really do?'

289
00:20:29,509 --> 00:20:30,889
Emma asked.

290
00:20:30,889 --> 00:20:36,890
'Well...' he said, in a funny accent, 'really,
I'm a comedian!'

291
00:20:36,890 --> 00:20:38,720
'A comedian!

292
00:20:38,720 --> 00:20:41,860
What kind of comedian?' asked Emma.

293
00:20:41,860 --> 00:20:45,860
'I do stand-up comedy in the evenings.

294
00:20:45,860 --> 00:20:51,059
I do gigs at small comedy clubs, but they
don't pay me very much.'

295
00:20:51,059 --> 00:20:52,490
Then he surprised her.

296
00:20:52,490 --> 00:20:58,489
He asked her to go on a date with him that
evening - to one of the clubs.

297
00:20:58,489 --> 00:21:03,489
She was touched, but she refused.

298
00:21:03,489 --> 00:21:07,279
In Bombay, Dexter Mayhew was writing a letter.

299
00:21:07,279 --> 00:21:10,009
Emma, Emma, Emma.

300
00:21:10,009 --> 00:21:11,450
How are you?

301
00:21:11,450 --> 00:21:13,370
What are you doing?

302
00:21:13,370 --> 00:21:15,409
I'm in Bombay and it's raining.

303
00:21:15,409 --> 00:21:20,029
It rains here even harder than it rains in
Edinburgh.

304
00:21:20,029 --> 00:21:23,779
It's too wet to go out so I'm staying in my
hotel room.

305
00:21:23,779 --> 00:21:27,389
I'm a bit drunk, are you surprised?

306
00:21:27,389 --> 00:21:34,399
I've seen some amazing things here in India
and I've taken thousands of photos.

307
00:21:34,399 --> 00:21:39,529
I'll show all of them to you very, very slowly
when I get back.

308
00:21:39,529 --> 00:21:44,799
I showed some of them to a TV producer I met
a few days ago.

309
00:21:44,799 --> 00:21:48,220
She's from London but she's making a film
here.

310
00:21:48,220 --> 00:21:54,429
I think she liked me - she wants me to call
her when I get back to England.

311
00:21:54,429 --> 00:21:58,030
Maybe she'll have a job for me in TV!

312
00:21:58,030 --> 00:22:03,090
I'll need to work soon and I'm banned from
teaching English to foreigners.

313
00:22:03,090 --> 00:22:06,190
I'm not sorry about that, I hated it.

314
00:22:06,190 --> 00:22:08,460
But I was treated very badly.

315
00:22:08,460 --> 00:22:10,659
That Danish girl was twenty-one!

316
00:22:10,659 --> 00:22:14,279
What are you doing now?

317
00:22:14,279 --> 00:22:17,749
Are you still sharing a flat with Tilly?

318
00:22:17,749 --> 00:22:20,749
Are you still working at that horrible restaurant?

319
00:22:20,749 --> 00:22:23,190
You need to leave that job, Emma.

320
00:22:23,190 --> 00:22:24,809
Listen to me, Emma!

321
00:22:24,809 --> 00:22:28,629
We need to do something about your life.

322
00:22:28,629 --> 00:22:33,399
I'm drunk at the moment, so I'm just going
to tell you what I think.

323
00:22:33,399 --> 00:22:36,039
You are clever.

324
00:22:36,039 --> 00:22:38,120
And you are beautiful.

325
00:22:38,120 --> 00:22:40,470
And you are loveable.

326
00:22:40,470 --> 00:22:42,919
And you are SEXY!

327
00:22:42,919 --> 00:22:45,750
You should be CONFIDENT!

328
00:22:45,750 --> 00:22:51,690
I want to take you away from boring people
like Tilly Killick and Callum O'Neill, the

329
00:22:51,690 --> 00:22:52,690
computer king.

330
00:22:52,690 --> 00:22:57,139
Would you like to live with me when I get
back to England?

331
00:22:57,139 --> 00:23:01,269
We would just be flatmates, of course.

332
00:23:01,269 --> 00:23:04,879
Now, here's my plan to change your life.

333
00:23:04,879 --> 00:23:06,399
Are you sitting down?

334
00:23:06,399 --> 00:23:10,029
The shock might knock you over!

335
00:23:10,029 --> 00:23:14,200
You should be here with me in India.

336
00:23:14,200 --> 00:23:16,450
I'm going to wire you some money.

337
00:23:16,450 --> 00:23:22,590
I've always wanted to wire someone some money
- it will make me feel important.

338
00:23:22,590 --> 00:23:25,109
Use the money to buy a plane ticket to Delhi.

339
00:23:25,109 --> 00:23:30,099
Then take a train to Agra and go to the Taj
Mahal.

340
00:23:30,099 --> 00:23:31,149
Have you heard of it?

341
00:23:31,149 --> 00:23:36,221
It's a big white building and it's named after
that Indian restaurant on the Lothian Road

342
00:23:36,221 --> 00:23:37,221
in Edinburgh.

343
00:23:37,221 --> 00:23:42,679
Be there exactly at noon on 1st August.

344
00:23:42,679 --> 00:23:47,320
Stand under the dome with a red rose in your
hand.

345
00:23:47,320 --> 00:23:48,929
I'll find you.

346
00:23:48,929 --> 00:23:52,269
I'll be carrying a white rose.

347
00:23:52,269 --> 00:23:57,179
Isn't that the greatest plan you've ever heard
in your life?

348
00:23:57,179 --> 00:24:02,070
Well, Emma, I'm still drunk, but it's stopped
raining.

349
00:24:02,070 --> 00:24:04,999
I'm going out now to meet some Dutch people
in a bar.

350
00:24:04,999 --> 00:24:07,330
I met them earlier today.

351
00:24:07,330 --> 00:24:08,690
They're all girls.

352
00:24:08,690 --> 00:24:10,470
They're nice.

353
00:24:10,470 --> 00:24:16,279
Don't forget - the Taj Mahal at noon on 1st
August.

354
00:24:16,279 --> 00:24:18,289
I'll find you.

355
00:24:18,289 --> 00:24:25,090
After he had finished the letter, Dexter took
a cold shower and soon he was feeling better.

356
00:24:25,090 --> 00:24:26,990
He was almost sober now.

357
00:24:26,990 --> 00:24:30,861
As he was dressing, he saw the letter, lying
on his bed.

358
00:24:30,861 --> 00:24:32,149
Should he send it?

359
00:24:32,149 --> 00:24:37,039
Suddenly he felt nervous.

360
00:24:37,039 --> 00:24:39,349
He'd called Emma clever and beautiful.

361
00:24:39,349 --> 00:24:42,379
He'd called her loveable.

362
00:24:42,379 --> 00:24:43,429
He'd called her sexy!

363
00:24:43,429 --> 00:24:46,960
He'd asked her to live with him.

364
00:24:46,960 --> 00:24:49,159
Would she be angry with him?

365
00:24:49,159 --> 00:24:50,859
Would she come to India?

366
00:24:50,859 --> 00:24:54,379
Did he really want to see her that much?

367
00:24:54,379 --> 00:24:57,499
He decided that he did.

368
00:24:57,499 --> 00:25:00,000
He decided that he would post the letter that
evening.

369
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:04,059
He put it in his pocket and he went out.

370
00:25:04,059 --> 00:25:10,929
Then he walked happily to the bar where his
new friends were waiting.

371
00:25:10,929 --> 00:25:15,879
At about nine o'clock that evening Dexter
left the bar with one of his Dutch friends

372
00:25:15,879 --> 00:25:17,499
- her name was Renee.

373
00:25:17,499 --> 00:25:23,169
As they left, they bumped into a large German
girl with a huge backpack.

374
00:25:23,169 --> 00:25:27,099
She was a student from Cologne and she was
called Heidi.

375
00:25:27,099 --> 00:25:34,799
She was tired and cross, and she swore quietly
at Dexter - it had been a long day.

376
00:25:34,799 --> 00:25:41,130
She crossed the room and sat down heavily
on the sofa where Dexter had been sitting.

377
00:25:41,130 --> 00:25:46,830
A few minutes later she moved sideways across
the sofa and felt something hard pressing

378
00:25:46,830 --> 00:25:48,619
into her leg.

379
00:25:48,619 --> 00:25:49,679
She swore again.

380
00:25:49,679 --> 00:25:55,719
There was an envelope between the cushions
of the sofa.

381
00:25:55,719 --> 00:25:58,149
She pulled it out and looked at it.

382
00:25:58,149 --> 00:26:04,139
Heidi opened the envelope and took out the
letter.

383
00:26:04,139 --> 00:26:06,669
She read it to the end.

384
00:26:06,669 --> 00:26:11,630
Her English wasn't very good, but she understood
most of the letter.

385
00:26:11,630 --> 00:26:15,179
She realized that it was important.

386
00:26:15,179 --> 00:26:18,299
It was the kind of letter she wanted someone
to write to her.

387
00:26:18,299 --> 00:26:21,649
It was a beautiful letter.

388
00:26:21,649 --> 00:26:24,899
She wanted this person called Emma to receive
it.

389
00:26:24,899 --> 00:26:28,359
But there was no name written on the envelope.

390
00:26:28,359 --> 00:26:32,399
And there was no address written on the letter.

391
00:26:32,399 --> 00:26:34,960
What could she do?

392
00:26:34,960 --> 00:26:55,049
Sadly, she realized there was nothing she
could do.

393
00:26:55,049 --> 00:26:57,690
CHAPTER FOUR
A Career Opportunity

394
00:26:57,690 --> 00:27:02,649
Monday, 15th July 1991

395
00:27:02,649 --> 00:27:06,590
Camden Town and Primrose Hill, London

396
00:27:06,590 --> 00:27:11,499
'Listen to me, please, everyone,' Scott McKenzie
shouted.

397
00:27:11,499 --> 00:27:16,369
'The restaurant opens in ten minutes and I
have some things to tell you.

398
00:27:16,369 --> 00:27:20,779
First, these are the special dishes for this
lunchtime.'

399
00:27:20,779 --> 00:27:27,519
Scott stopped, looked around him and then
went on when his staff had stopped talking.

400
00:27:27,519 --> 00:27:32,279
'Today's special soup is corn chowder.

401
00:27:32,279 --> 00:27:35,279
And the special burrito is turkey.'

402
00:27:35,279 --> 00:27:41,219
'Turkey's not a good idea in July,' said Ian
Whitehead wearily.

403
00:27:41,219 --> 00:27:45,330
'Turkey's really for Christmas.'

404
00:27:45,330 --> 00:27:47,470
He shook his head in despair.

405
00:27:47,470 --> 00:27:50,349
This made Emma Morley laugh.

406
00:27:50,349 --> 00:27:54,999
Ian was now Emma's best friend, but she rarely
laughed at what he said.

407
00:27:54,999 --> 00:27:58,409
Scott looked at the two of them.

408
00:27:58,409 --> 00:28:02,990
'Ian, you can clean the toilets today,' Scott
said.

409
00:28:02,990 --> 00:28:07,320
'Emma, I need to talk to you in my office.'

410
00:28:07,320 --> 00:28:11,320
Emma followed the manager into his office
and sat down.

411
00:28:11,320 --> 00:28:14,349
'I'll come straight to the point,' Scott said.

412
00:28:14,349 --> 00:28:18,029
'I'm leaving Loco Caliente soon.

413
00:28:18,029 --> 00:28:22,840
I'm going to be the manager of a big, new
restaurant in West London.

414
00:28:22,840 --> 00:28:25,919
Do you want to be the manager here when I
go?

415
00:28:25,919 --> 00:28:28,299
It's a good career opportunity.

416
00:28:28,299 --> 00:28:33,440
Head office wants someone who isn't going
anywhere.

417
00:28:33,440 --> 00:28:40,349
Someone who won't go away travelling or leave
suddenly to start a more exciting job.'

418
00:28:40,349 --> 00:28:42,350
And suddenly, Emma was crying.

419
00:28:42,350 --> 00:28:44,330
'What's wrong, Emma?'

420
00:28:44,330 --> 00:28:45,649
Scott asked.

421
00:28:45,649 --> 00:28:48,289
'Has somebody upset you?'

422
00:28:48,289 --> 00:28:51,599
'No, it's all right, Scott.

423
00:28:51,599 --> 00:28:54,700
It's really nothing,' Emma told him.

424
00:28:54,700 --> 00:28:59,869
'Don't worry, I'll be fine in a minute.'

425
00:28:59,869 --> 00:29:02,470
'Go and rest in the staffroom,' said Scott
kindly.

426
00:29:02,470 --> 00:29:04,619
'Give me your answer about the job tomorrow.'

427
00:29:04,619 --> 00:29:10,099
A few minutes later Emma was alone in the
staffroom.

428
00:29:10,099 --> 00:29:12,339
She looked around her in despair.

429
00:29:12,339 --> 00:29:15,879
She knew that she couldn't leave her job.

430
00:29:15,879 --> 00:29:20,980
She had to spend all her money on rent, so
she needed to take the manager's job.

431
00:29:20,980 --> 00:29:25,749
But she didn't want to be a restaurant manager
all her life.

432
00:29:25,749 --> 00:29:31,609
She still wanted to be a writer, or perhaps
a film-maker, or a painter.

433
00:29:31,609 --> 00:29:35,379
She wanted to be something in the arts.

434
00:29:35,379 --> 00:29:42,559
She spent lots of time writing - she mostly
wrote poems these days.

435
00:29:42,559 --> 00:29:45,559
But nothing was working well for her.

436
00:29:45,559 --> 00:29:49,429
Nobody wanted to publish her poems.

437
00:29:49,429 --> 00:29:53,940
Emma knew that her mother was still trying
to find jobs for her in Yorkshire.

438
00:29:53,940 --> 00:29:57,210
Some days, she thought she would go back there.

439
00:29:57,210 --> 00:30:03,330
'I've had a battle with London and London
has won,' she told herself.

440
00:30:03,330 --> 00:30:06,750
But she wasn't ready to stop fighting yet.

441
00:30:06,750 --> 00:30:10,409
She needed to be in London.

442
00:30:10,409 --> 00:30:14,610
Emma opened her handbag and took out her special
notebook.

443
00:30:14,610 --> 00:30:19,889
The book had a beautiful cover and lovely,
thick, white paper.

444
00:30:19,889 --> 00:30:23,070
It was where Emma wrote her poems.

445
00:30:23,070 --> 00:30:25,960
Now she took out her best pen.

446
00:30:25,960 --> 00:30:31,589
She thought for minute, then she started to
write a new poem about how she felt.

447
00:30:31,589 --> 00:30:38,610
The poem she wrote was quite short and she
knew it was really bad.

448
00:30:38,610 --> 00:30:44,429
She turned back through the pages of the book
and found an earlier poem called Daybreak

449
00:30:44,429 --> 00:30:45,429
in Edinburgh.

450
00:30:45,429 --> 00:30:46,429
She read it.

451
00:30:46,429 --> 00:30:48,679
We lie here in the

452
00:30:48,679 --> 00:30:52,289
Narrow bed and talk

453
00:30:52,289 --> 00:30:53,289
About the future.

454
00:30:53,289 --> 00:30:54,289
I

455
00:30:54,289 --> 00:30:55,809
Look at him and think

456
00:30:55,809 --> 00:30:58,749
'Handsome' - stupid word - and I

457
00:30:58,749 --> 00:31:00,509
Ask myself the

458
00:31:00,509 --> 00:31:01,690
Hardest question,

459
00:31:01,690 --> 00:31:03,940
'Might it be the real

460
00:31:03,940 --> 00:31:05,460
Thing, this time?

461
00:31:05,460 --> 00:31:08,510
Outside the birds begin to sing and

462
00:31:08,510 --> 00:31:13,309
Sunlight warms the curtain.

463
00:31:13,309 --> 00:31:15,809
Emma looked carefully at what she had written.

464
00:31:15,809 --> 00:31:23,869
'Can I really make the bad things in my life
seem better by writing about them?' she wondered.

465
00:31:23,869 --> 00:31:29,380
She had just decided that she could not do
that because that poem was rubbish too, when

466
00:31:29,380 --> 00:31:32,049
Ian came into the staffroom.

467
00:31:32,049 --> 00:31:35,119
Ian looked angry and unhappy.

468
00:31:35,119 --> 00:31:41,059
'Emma,' he said, 'your friend is in the restaurant
again the handsome one.

469
00:31:41,059 --> 00:31:43,169
He wants to see you.

470
00:31:43,169 --> 00:31:47,700
He's with a girl a different one this time.'

471
00:31:47,700 --> 00:31:51,980
Ian had seen several of Dexter's girlfriends.

472
00:31:51,980 --> 00:31:56,309
Dexter obviously liked to show them to Emma
and this clearly upset her.

473
00:31:56,309 --> 00:31:58,580
It upset Ian too.

474
00:31:58,580 --> 00:32:01,989
'He's a monster, Emma,' Ian said.

475
00:32:01,989 --> 00:32:07,089
'No, he's not a monster, he's just an idiot.'

476
00:32:07,089 --> 00:32:11,350
Emma sighed and went out into the restaurant.

477
00:32:11,350 --> 00:32:17,489
Dexter was with a tall, thin girl with black
hair and expensive black clothes.

478
00:32:17,489 --> 00:32:22,269
They were reading the menu aloud to each other
and laughing about it.

479
00:32:22,269 --> 00:32:23,610
'Hello, Emma!'

480
00:32:23,610 --> 00:32:26,589
Dexter said when he saw her.

481
00:32:26,589 --> 00:32:28,679
'This is Naomi.

482
00:32:28,679 --> 00:32:30,249
Will you have a drink with us?'

483
00:32:30,249 --> 00:32:33,549
His voice told Emma that he was drunk.

484
00:32:33,549 --> 00:32:39,099
'I can't do that, Dex, I'm working,' Emma
replied.

485
00:32:39,099 --> 00:32:40,099
'Goodbye.'

486
00:32:40,099 --> 00:32:42,489
She turned away and walked back to the staffroom.

487
00:32:42,489 --> 00:32:49,879
Later, before leaving the restaurant, Dexter
left a handwritten note on his table.

488
00:32:49,879 --> 00:32:56,029
Later in the day, after Emma had finished
work, she found Dexter lying on the grass

489
00:32:56,029 --> 00:32:57,929
on Primrose Hill, a mile away.

490
00:32:57,929 --> 00:33:02,730
The evening sun was warm and he was almost
asleep.

491
00:33:02,730 --> 00:33:06,630
A half-empty wine bottle told her the reason.

492
00:33:06,630 --> 00:33:08,870
Emma kicked his leg.

493
00:33:08,870 --> 00:33:14,210
'Don't do that to me, Dexter,' she said angrily.

494
00:33:14,210 --> 00:33:17,239
'Don't bring people into the restaurant to
laugh at me.

495
00:33:17,239 --> 00:33:22,159
If you ever do that again, it's the end of
our friendship.'

496
00:33:22,159 --> 00:33:24,610
'I'm sorry, Em,' Dexter said.

497
00:33:24,610 --> 00:33:26,419
'I'm really sorry.

498
00:33:26,419 --> 00:33:28,820
I apologize.'

499
00:33:28,820 --> 00:33:33,820
Emma looked at him and decided that he meant
what he said - for now.

500
00:33:33,820 --> 00:33:35,610
She sat down beside him.

501
00:33:35,610 --> 00:33:42,570
'Won't your girlfriend be angry if she finds
out that you left a note asking me to meet

502
00:33:42,570 --> 00:33:43,570
you?'

503
00:33:43,570 --> 00:33:44,570
she asked.

504
00:33:44,570 --> 00:33:49,879
'Oh, Naomi isn't really my girlfriend,' Dexter
replied happily.

505
00:33:49,879 --> 00:33:52,850
'She's just someone I go out with sometimes.'

506
00:33:52,850 --> 00:33:56,789
'I'm sorry, then,' said Emma.

507
00:33:56,789 --> 00:34:01,379
'Clearly, I don't mean girlfriend, I mean
victim.'

508
00:34:01,379 --> 00:34:03,839
She spoke sadly.

509
00:34:03,839 --> 00:34:09,050
And she thought, 'Em and Dex, Dex and Em.

510
00:34:09,050 --> 00:34:13,980
No, it's never going to happen now.'

511
00:34:13,980 --> 00:34:16,640
She picked up the bottle of wine and drank
from it.

512
00:34:16,640 --> 00:34:22,480
Dexter looked at her and he felt warm inside.

513
00:34:22,480 --> 00:34:27,159
He often thought that Emma Morley was the
best person he'd ever known.

514
00:34:27,159 --> 00:34:30,589
But he'd never really told her that.

515
00:34:30,589 --> 00:34:33,339
And he didn't tell her that now.

516
00:34:33,339 --> 00:34:54,419
For some reason, he couldn't make himself
tell her that.

517
00:34:54,419 --> 00:34:56,250
CHAPTER FIVE
The Rules

518
00:34:56,250 --> 00:35:01,680
Wednesday, 15th July 1992

519
00:35:01,680 --> 00:35:03,769
The Greek islands

520
00:35:03,769 --> 00:35:10,450
Dexter and Emma were lying sleepily on the
deck of a small ferry.

521
00:35:10,450 --> 00:35:16,900
The two friends were travelling from the Greek
island of Rhodes to a smaller island.

522
00:35:16,900 --> 00:35:21,410
They were going to stay there for a week and
they were both feeling happy.

523
00:35:21,410 --> 00:35:25,609
Life was changing for them.

524
00:35:25,609 --> 00:35:31,599
After a year as manager at Loco Caliente,
Emma had left her job.

525
00:35:31,599 --> 00:35:35,480
In September she was going to start a college
course.

526
00:35:35,480 --> 00:35:39,490
She was going to train to be a schoolteacher.

527
00:35:39,490 --> 00:35:42,089
And Dexter had a job now.

528
00:35:42,089 --> 00:35:45,380
He was working for a television company.

529
00:35:45,380 --> 00:35:52,310
He'd started with small responsibilities - making
the tea, doing research for producers.

530
00:35:52,310 --> 00:35:55,660
But now he was working as an interviewer.

531
00:35:55,660 --> 00:36:03,090
He interviewed pop stars and actors on a programme
called The Bigger Picture.

532
00:36:03,090 --> 00:36:09,359
He had a posh flat in Belsize Park - an expensive
part of north London.

533
00:36:09,359 --> 00:36:12,920
He wore expensive designer clothes.

534
00:36:12,920 --> 00:36:18,299
And he had a new girlfriend, his fourth one
after Naomi.

535
00:36:18,299 --> 00:36:22,230
She was a beautiful and successful model.

536
00:36:22,230 --> 00:36:29,210
Emma didn't really enjoy Dexter's television
appearances, but she always watched them.

537
00:36:29,210 --> 00:36:35,640
For The Bigger Picture, Dexter had invented
a new character for himself.

538
00:36:35,640 --> 00:36:38,290
He was a 'man of the people'.

539
00:36:38,290 --> 00:36:44,660
When he interviewed pop stars and actors,
he spoke with a cockney accent.

540
00:36:44,660 --> 00:36:49,700
Emma had never enjoyed Dexter's version of
a Yorkshire accent and she thought that his

541
00:36:49,700 --> 00:36:52,180
'cockney' voice was even worse.

542
00:36:52,180 --> 00:36:59,019
Emma liked Dexter to know that she wasn't
impressed by his television career.

543
00:36:59,019 --> 00:37:02,099
She told him this often.

544
00:37:02,099 --> 00:37:04,180
But all that was back in London.

545
00:37:04,180 --> 00:37:06,079
Today they were happy.

546
00:37:06,079 --> 00:37:11,680
Today, they were on a ferry among the beautiful
Greek islands.

547
00:37:11,680 --> 00:37:14,650
They were on holiday together.

548
00:37:14,650 --> 00:37:18,829
It had been surprisingly easy to arrange this
trip.

549
00:37:18,829 --> 00:37:24,420
Dexter's girlfriend was very self-confident,
so she had no problems about his holiday with

550
00:37:24,420 --> 00:37:26,720
another woman.

551
00:37:26,720 --> 00:37:32,270
And Emma occasionally slept with people but
still didn't have a regular boyfriend.

552
00:37:32,270 --> 00:37:38,809
So they had made their plans together and
they had decided on some rules of behaviour

553
00:37:38,809 --> 00:37:41,710
for the holiday.

554
00:37:41,710 --> 00:37:43,640
The Rules:

555
00:37:43,640 --> 00:37:46,539
One: Separate bedrooms.

556
00:37:46,539 --> 00:37:49,440
Two: No flirting.

557
00:37:49,440 --> 00:37:53,309
Three: No sleeping together.

558
00:37:53,309 --> 00:37:56,210
Four: No nudity.

559
00:37:56,210 --> 00:38:00,079
Five: No board games.

560
00:38:00,079 --> 00:38:03,880
Emma had decided on the first four rules.

561
00:38:03,880 --> 00:38:06,540
Dexter had fought back with Rule Five.

562
00:38:06,540 --> 00:38:12,529
Emma enjoyed playing board games, but Dexter
hated them.

563
00:38:12,529 --> 00:38:20,970
The Rules had to be obeyed, Emma told herself
now, lying sleepily on the deck of the ferry.

564
00:38:20,970 --> 00:38:23,089
The Rules made this holiday possible.

565
00:38:23,089 --> 00:38:27,859
But Emma wondered if Dexter was going to be
able to obey them.

566
00:38:27,859 --> 00:38:31,190
And she wondered if she was going to be able
to obey them.

567
00:38:31,190 --> 00:38:36,470
They were half asleep when they heard an English
voice.

568
00:38:36,470 --> 00:38:39,140
'It's him,' said a man.

569
00:38:39,140 --> 00:38:41,819
'He's on TV on Fridays.'

570
00:38:41,819 --> 00:38:44,020
'Oh, yes,' said a girl.

571
00:38:44,020 --> 00:38:46,369
'He's called Dexter something.

572
00:38:46,369 --> 00:38:51,660
You are that man who's on TV, aren't you?'

573
00:38:51,660 --> 00:38:54,540
She was speaking to Dexter now.

574
00:38:54,540 --> 00:38:57,349
And he was wide awake.

575
00:38:57,349 --> 00:38:58,349
'Yep.

576
00:38:58,349 --> 00:39:03,140
On 'oliday, are ya?' said Dexter in his pretend-cockney
accent.

577
00:39:03,140 --> 00:39:07,589
'Yeah,' said the girl.

578
00:39:07,589 --> 00:39:11,720
Dexter continued talking to her and didn't
take any notice of the man.

579
00:39:11,720 --> 00:39:14,769
The girl was clearly impressed.

580
00:39:14,769 --> 00:39:19,880
'Dexter, why do you speak like that?'

581
00:39:19,880 --> 00:39:21,950
Emma asked when the couple had gone.

582
00:39:21,950 --> 00:39:27,470
'You aren't a Londoner and you went to Winchester
College.'

583
00:39:27,470 --> 00:39:34,640
'The TV viewers won't connect with me if I
don't seem like them,' Dexter explained.

584
00:39:34,640 --> 00:39:37,460
'Not many of our viewers went to Winchester.'

585
00:39:37,460 --> 00:39:41,920
'That's a very bad reason,' said Emma.

586
00:39:41,920 --> 00:39:45,650
'And you've broken Rule Two already.

587
00:39:45,650 --> 00:39:49,630
You were flirting with that girl.'

588
00:39:49,630 --> 00:39:55,130
Emma was sitting at a table outside a small
cafe on the island and drinking coffee.

589
00:39:55,130 --> 00:39:58,640
Dexter had gone to find them somewhere to
stay.

590
00:39:58,640 --> 00:40:05,980
'Don't forget, we need two rooms,' Emma had
shouted after him as he set off.

591
00:40:05,980 --> 00:40:09,950
And he'd looked back at her and shouted, 'Of
course we do!'

592
00:40:09,950 --> 00:40:15,500
'She looks so lovely these days,' he told
himself.

593
00:40:15,500 --> 00:40:17,800
'It's the contact lenses.

594
00:40:17,800 --> 00:40:22,460
I hated those thick glasses she used to wear.

595
00:40:22,460 --> 00:40:24,230
But now she looks great.

596
00:40:24,230 --> 00:40:27,539
These rules aren't going to make life easy.'

597
00:40:27,539 --> 00:40:34,859
But an hour later, when he returned to the
cafe, Dexter seemed very pleased.

598
00:40:34,859 --> 00:40:38,530
'There's some bad news, Emma,' he said.

599
00:40:38,530 --> 00:40:41,710
'I could only find one room on the island.

600
00:40:41,710 --> 00:40:46,800
It's a wonderful room, but it only has one
bed.

601
00:40:46,800 --> 00:40:49,980
But it's a very large bed.'

602
00:40:49,980 --> 00:40:56,290
Emma believed that Dexter hadn't tried to
find two rooms.

603
00:40:56,290 --> 00:41:00,299
She believed that Dexter had never meant to
find two rooms.

604
00:41:00,299 --> 00:41:02,730
And of course, she was correct.

605
00:41:02,730 --> 00:41:08,050
'All right, let's go and see the room,' Emma
said wearily.

606
00:41:08,050 --> 00:41:12,539
But when they got there, Emma loved the room.

607
00:41:12,539 --> 00:41:14,270
The bed was a large one.

608
00:41:14,270 --> 00:41:17,069
And there was a balcony.

609
00:41:17,069 --> 00:41:21,779
They could stand on it and look out over the
sea.

610
00:41:21,779 --> 00:41:26,849
'The room is fine, Dexter,' Emma said.

611
00:41:26,849 --> 00:41:29,029
'We'll stay here.

612
00:41:29,029 --> 00:41:34,769
And you'll stay on your own side of the bed,
won't you?'

613
00:41:34,769 --> 00:41:38,109
Late that evening, Dexter and Emma walked
down to the beach.

614
00:41:38,109 --> 00:41:43,759
The sun had disappeared and no one else was
there.

615
00:41:43,759 --> 00:41:45,700
'Shall we swim, Emma?'

616
00:41:45,700 --> 00:41:46,700
Dexter said.

617
00:41:46,700 --> 00:41:50,029
By now, Emma could read Dexter's mind.

618
00:41:50,029 --> 00:41:51,870
She could almost hear it working.

619
00:41:51,870 --> 00:41:58,579
This wasn't difficult, because Dexter only
thought about a small number of things.

620
00:41:58,579 --> 00:42:07,440
'We don't have swimsuits with us,' Emma replied
very slowly, speaking in the way people speak

621
00:42:07,440 --> 00:42:08,890
to young children.

622
00:42:08,890 --> 00:42:10,950
'We don't need swimsuits.

623
00:42:10,950 --> 00:42:13,369
There's no one here,' Dexter said.

624
00:42:13,369 --> 00:42:16,599
'I understand you too well, Dex,' Emma said.

625
00:42:16,599 --> 00:42:22,430
'You just want to get my clothes off, don't
you?'

626
00:42:22,430 --> 00:42:24,740
Dexter was silent.

627
00:42:24,740 --> 00:42:30,359
'You swim if you want to, Dexter,' Emma went
on.

628
00:42:30,359 --> 00:42:34,640
'I'm not going to show my body to the world.

629
00:42:34,640 --> 00:42:37,559
And you've forgotten Rule Four.'

630
00:42:37,559 --> 00:42:44,079
A moment later, Dexter had taken off all his
clothes and was running into the sea.

631
00:42:44,079 --> 00:42:45,960
Emma suddenly felt stupid.

632
00:42:45,960 --> 00:42:51,609
'Why can't I be free and uncomplicated like
Dexter?'

633
00:42:51,609 --> 00:42:53,490
she asked herself.

634
00:42:53,490 --> 00:42:57,890
'Why do I care who sees me?'

635
00:42:57,890 --> 00:43:03,089
She quickly took off her own clothes and she
too ran naked into the sea.

636
00:43:03,089 --> 00:43:06,769
Soon she was standing next to her friend.

637
00:43:06,769 --> 00:43:09,530
He turned to face her.

638
00:43:09,530 --> 00:43:13,770
'Can we talk about Rule Three, Em?'

639
00:43:13,770 --> 00:43:15,690
Dexter said gently.

640
00:43:15,690 --> 00:43:19,010
'You see, I really want you.'

641
00:43:19,010 --> 00:43:23,760
For a moment, Emma felt wonderful.

642
00:43:23,760 --> 00:43:25,960
He had said it at last.

643
00:43:25,960 --> 00:43:32,700
And it was going to happen, here and now,
in the beautiful warm sea.

644
00:43:32,700 --> 00:43:36,150
Dex and Em, Em and Dex.

645
00:43:36,150 --> 00:43:39,670
It was going to happen.

646
00:43:39,670 --> 00:43:42,930
And then Dexter said the wrong thing.

647
00:43:42,930 --> 00:43:46,450
'Of course, it isn't personal.

648
00:43:46,450 --> 00:43:50,740
I want nearly every woman that I meet,' he
added.

649
00:43:50,740 --> 00:43:52,759
'That's my problem.

650
00:43:52,759 --> 00:43:55,450
I can't escape it.

651
00:43:55,450 --> 00:43:58,150
It's like a nightmare!'

652
00:43:58,150 --> 00:44:02,190
'Oh, poor Dexter,' Emma said angrily.

653
00:44:02,190 --> 00:44:06,240
'I feel really sorry for you.'

654
00:44:06,240 --> 00:44:09,890
She was angry with Dexter and she was angry
with herself.

655
00:44:09,890 --> 00:44:13,530
'You're a stupid, stupid woman,' she told
herself.

656
00:44:13,530 --> 00:44:17,779
'You're stupid for thinking that he really
cared about you.'

657
00:44:17,779 --> 00:44:23,029
But a moment later, it was Dexter who was
angry.

658
00:44:23,029 --> 00:44:26,019
He was looking over Emma's shoulder at the
beach.

659
00:44:26,019 --> 00:44:30,390
A boy was stealing his clothes.

660
00:44:30,390 --> 00:44:31,390
'Stop!

661
00:44:31,390 --> 00:44:32,770
Don't do that!'

662
00:44:32,770 --> 00:44:34,430
Dexter shouted.

663
00:44:34,430 --> 00:44:36,680
He started to run towards the beach.

664
00:44:36,680 --> 00:44:43,430
'Those trousers cost me two hundred pounds!'
he shouted at Emma, who was laughing.

665
00:44:43,430 --> 00:44:50,829
When they reached the beach, the boy, and
Dexter's expensive clothes, had disappeared.

666
00:44:50,829 --> 00:44:54,690
He hadn't taken Emma's clothes.

667
00:44:54,690 --> 00:45:01,359
When she had stopped laughing, Emma got dressed
and Dexter found a torn, blue, plastic bag

668
00:45:01,359 --> 00:45:03,200
on the beach.

669
00:45:03,200 --> 00:45:07,720
He held this in front of him as they ran back
to their room.

670
00:45:07,720 --> 00:45:11,760
On the way, they passed the English couple
they had met on the ferry.

671
00:45:11,760 --> 00:45:15,549
'I like the bag,' the man said.

672
00:45:15,549 --> 00:45:19,020
'It's a great colour.'

673
00:45:19,020 --> 00:45:20,650
He laughed mockingly.

674
00:45:20,650 --> 00:45:22,819
Dexter didn't reply.

675
00:45:22,819 --> 00:45:27,029
But when they got back to their room, Dexter's
anger had gone.

676
00:45:27,029 --> 00:45:29,529
It was a beautiful evening.

677
00:45:29,529 --> 00:45:34,620
And soon, the stars were bright in the sky.

678
00:45:34,620 --> 00:45:39,829
He and Emma had some food, then they got into
the bed and lay in the dark.

679
00:45:39,829 --> 00:45:46,589
They didn't touch each other, and they knew
that their friendship was unchanged.

680
00:45:46,589 --> 00:45:50,619
'Tell me a secret, Em,' Dexter said.

681
00:45:50,619 --> 00:45:54,880
'Tell me something about yourself that I don't
know.'

682
00:45:54,880 --> 00:46:02,069
'Well, I don't want to make you more arrogant
than you already are,' Emma replied.

683
00:46:02,069 --> 00:46:05,119
'But here's something you didn't know.

684
00:46:05,119 --> 00:46:11,990
Before I first talked to you, when we were
students, I was in love with you.

685
00:46:11,990 --> 00:46:15,140
And I used to write poems about you.'

686
00:46:15,140 --> 00:46:19,180
'That was before you knew me,' Dexter said.

687
00:46:19,180 --> 00:46:20,751
'Aren't you in love with me now?'

688
00:46:20,751 --> 00:46:29,119
'Oh, now - things are quite different now,'
said Emma.

689
00:46:29,119 --> 00:46:33,579
When she said that, Dexter started thinking
about his own secrets.

690
00:46:33,579 --> 00:46:38,519
He'd never told Emma that he'd once slept
with Tilly Killick.

691
00:46:38,519 --> 00:46:43,280
It had happened when he was visiting the flat
Emma and Tilly shared.

692
00:46:43,280 --> 00:46:45,630
Emma had gone out to the shops for an hour.

693
00:46:45,630 --> 00:46:50,250
He was never going to tell her about that.

694
00:46:50,250 --> 00:46:57,190
He didn't know that Emma knew about it already
and it wasn't a secret at all.

695
00:46:57,190 --> 00:47:03,589
'Tell me about those poems,' Dexter said quietly,
after a few minutes.

696
00:47:03,589 --> 00:47:06,549
'What rhymed with Dexter?'

697
00:47:06,549 --> 00:47:08,829
'Monster,' Emma replied quickly.

698
00:47:08,829 --> 00:47:11,680
'It's a half-rhyme.'

699
00:47:11,680 --> 00:47:19,170
'Em,' Dexter said a few minutes later, 'how
many rules did I break today?'

700
00:47:19,170 --> 00:47:20,809
'Three,' Emma said.

701
00:47:20,809 --> 00:47:23,960
'You broke Rules One, Two and Four.'

702
00:47:23,960 --> 00:47:29,130
'And we nearly broke Rule Three,' Dexter thought.

703
00:47:29,130 --> 00:47:32,119
'But we have eight more days.

704
00:47:32,119 --> 00:47:35,130
Anything can happen in eight days.'

705
00:47:35,130 --> 00:47:40,269
'Well, at least we didn't play any board games,'
he said aloud.

706
00:47:40,269 --> 00:48:02,510
Emma was asleep.

707
00:48:02,510 --> 00:48:05,640
CHAPTER SIX
Poison

708
00:48:05,640 --> 00:48:11,099
Thursday, 15th July 1993

709
00:48:11,099 --> 00:48:16,140
Belsize Park, London and Oxfordshire

710
00:48:16,140 --> 00:48:19,570
Dexter Mayhew was sitting in his flat in Belsize
Park.

711
00:48:19,570 --> 00:48:24,690
It was 10 AM and Dexter was very drunk.

712
00:48:24,690 --> 00:48:29,299
He had been drinking all night with some new
friends.

713
00:48:29,299 --> 00:48:34,829
Now that he worked in television, lots of
people wanted to know Dexter.

714
00:48:34,829 --> 00:48:39,579
They all wanted to hear his stories about
the famous people that he interviewed.

715
00:48:39,579 --> 00:48:42,210
They all wanted to drink with him.

716
00:48:42,210 --> 00:48:46,309
So he was often drunk these days.

717
00:48:46,309 --> 00:48:50,690
Usually, being drunk in the mornings didn't
matter.

718
00:48:50,690 --> 00:48:55,400
Dexter worked in the afternoons and evenings
and he was always sober by then.

719
00:48:55,400 --> 00:49:02,680
But this morning, the morning of 15th July,
it mattered very much.

720
00:49:02,680 --> 00:49:07,619
Today he had to go to his parents' house in
the country, in Oxfordshire.

721
00:49:07,619 --> 00:49:09,660
He was already late.

722
00:49:09,660 --> 00:49:14,880
He knew, in part of his mind, that he wanted
to be late.

723
00:49:14,880 --> 00:49:20,829
In fact, in that part of his mind, he didn't
want to go at all.

724
00:49:20,829 --> 00:49:25,900
Because today, thinking about his parents
made him want to scream.

725
00:49:25,900 --> 00:49:33,950
Dexter's mother, at forty-nine, was fifteen
years younger than his father.

726
00:49:33,950 --> 00:49:37,420
Dexter liked his father and they usually got
on well together.

727
00:49:37,420 --> 00:49:41,900
But his feelings about his mother were quite
different.

728
00:49:41,900 --> 00:49:46,920
Dexter loved his mother more than anyone in
the world.

729
00:49:46,920 --> 00:49:52,690
But now his mother was dying and Dexter knew
that she couldn't live much longer.

730
00:49:52,690 --> 00:49:56,930
He needed to see her, but he was afraid.

731
00:49:56,930 --> 00:50:00,180
He was afraid to see how close to death she
was.

732
00:50:00,180 --> 00:50:04,700
So this morning, he needed to be strong.

733
00:50:04,700 --> 00:50:08,660
He needed to make himself drive to his childhood
home.

734
00:50:08,660 --> 00:50:13,980
And he needed to make himself behave normally
when he got there.

735
00:50:13,980 --> 00:50:19,240
Dexter looked at the large parcel, wrapped
in brightly coloured paper, which he'd put

736
00:50:19,240 --> 00:50:20,599
next to his front door.

737
00:50:20,599 --> 00:50:26,200
He'd put it there so that he wouldn't forget
it when he went out, even if he was drunk.

738
00:50:26,200 --> 00:50:33,160
The parcel was a present for his mother from
his good friend Emma Morley.

739
00:50:33,160 --> 00:50:39,220
Emma and his mother were very different people,
but when they had met they had always enjoyed

740
00:50:39,220 --> 00:50:41,369
each other's company.

741
00:50:41,369 --> 00:50:47,590
And Stephen and Alison Mayhew had guessed
that Emma was a good friend to their son.

742
00:50:47,590 --> 00:50:55,890
They hadn't really been offended at all when
Emma called Stephen 'a bourgeois fascist'.

743
00:50:55,890 --> 00:50:59,710
Remembering this, for a moment Dexter wanted
to phone Emma.

744
00:50:59,710 --> 00:51:07,690
The two of them had still never touched each
other, but he knew that she was his best friend.

745
00:51:07,690 --> 00:51:12,619
Suddenly, he wanted to tell her that she was
a dear, wonderful person.

746
00:51:12,619 --> 00:51:19,420
And he wanted to tell her how unhappy he was
about his mother's terrible illness.

747
00:51:19,420 --> 00:51:22,660
But he knew what Emma would say.

748
00:51:22,660 --> 00:51:28,250
'She'll know I'm drunk as soon as I start
to speak,' he told himself.

749
00:51:28,250 --> 00:51:33,980
'She'll tell me that I mustn't drive.'

750
00:51:33,980 --> 00:51:37,660
Dexter picked up his car keys and collected
Emma's parcel.

751
00:51:37,660 --> 00:51:43,319
He locked the door of his flat behind him
and walked to his expensive, green sports

752
00:51:43,319 --> 00:51:46,130
car.

753
00:51:46,130 --> 00:51:50,119
An hour later, Dexter was still worrying about
his dying mother.

754
00:51:50,119 --> 00:51:55,420
But he also knew that he was lucky to be alive
himself.

755
00:51:55,420 --> 00:52:01,579
He had fallen asleep for a moment and had
almost crashed his car into a big truck.

756
00:52:01,579 --> 00:52:07,089
He could still hear the noise of the truck's
horn in his aching head.

757
00:52:07,089 --> 00:52:13,170
He wasn't far from his parents' house now,
but he had to stop for a while.

758
00:52:13,170 --> 00:52:16,839
He slowed down and drove into a pub cark park.

759
00:52:16,839 --> 00:52:21,349
It was a pub which he had often visited when
he was young.

760
00:52:21,349 --> 00:52:27,400
He bought a glass of vodka and a glass of
beer and sat down.

761
00:52:27,400 --> 00:52:33,420
He drank quickly and soon he was feeling better.

762
00:52:33,420 --> 00:52:36,880
He walked outside into the sunlight and got
into his car.

763
00:52:36,880 --> 00:52:43,499
In less than twenty minutes, he parked in
front of his parents' house, just as his father

764
00:52:43,499 --> 00:52:45,529
opened the front door.

765
00:52:45,529 --> 00:52:52,099
'I'd hoped you were coming earlier,' his father
said as Dexter got out of the car.

766
00:52:52,099 --> 00:52:58,580
He looked angry and when Dexter tried to kiss
him on the cheeks, he moved quickly away.

767
00:52:58,580 --> 00:53:03,680
At the television studios, everyone kissed
everyone else on the cheeks.

768
00:53:03,680 --> 00:53:09,500
Dexter had forgotten for a moment that his
father lived in a different world.

769
00:53:09,500 --> 00:53:14,880
'Your mother hoped you were coming earlier
too,' Stephen Mayhew added.

770
00:53:14,880 --> 00:53:18,990
He looked carefully at his son, then he sighed
deeply.

771
00:53:18,990 --> 00:53:23,359
'I'm sorry - I'm so sorry,' Dexter said unhappily.

772
00:53:23,359 --> 00:53:25,790
'How is she, Dad?'

773
00:53:25,790 --> 00:53:30,109
'You need to ask her that yourself,' Mr Mayhew
said.

774
00:53:30,109 --> 00:53:33,309
'Go up to her room now.

775
00:53:33,309 --> 00:53:36,549
I'll make us some lunch.'

776
00:53:36,549 --> 00:53:40,749
Dexter walked slowly up the stairs, carrying
Emma's present.

777
00:53:40,749 --> 00:53:45,329
He opened the door of his mother's bedroom
and went nervously inside.

778
00:53:45,329 --> 00:53:49,220
Alison Mayhew was sitting up in her bed.

779
00:53:49,220 --> 00:53:53,390
She was very thin and she looked very tired
and ill.

780
00:53:53,390 --> 00:53:57,140
But she smiled when she saw her son.

781
00:53:57,140 --> 00:53:58,430
'A present!

782
00:53:58,430 --> 00:54:01,270
What have you brought me?'

783
00:54:01,270 --> 00:54:02,270
she asked.

784
00:54:02,270 --> 00:54:06,369
'The present is from Emma,' Dexter said.

785
00:54:06,369 --> 00:54:08,890
'Let's open it.'

786
00:54:08,890 --> 00:54:17,789
The parcel contained books - long, serious
books - Edith Wharton, Scott Fitzgerald, Raymond

787
00:54:17,789 --> 00:54:18,789
Chandler.

788
00:54:18,789 --> 00:54:22,730
'How kind she is,' Alison Mayhew said.

789
00:54:22,730 --> 00:54:25,290
'I'm very grateful to Emma.

790
00:54:25,290 --> 00:54:33,430
But please suggest to her that short stories
might be more useful in future.'

791
00:54:33,430 --> 00:54:38,749
Dexter tried to laugh, but inside his head
he was screaming.

792
00:54:38,749 --> 00:54:45,279
A few minutes later, he went downstairs to
the kitchen, where his father was making lunch.

793
00:54:45,279 --> 00:54:51,079
Dexter picked up a glass of wine and drank
it quickly, then he refilled the glass.

794
00:54:51,079 --> 00:54:55,750
'Dexter, please be careful,' his father said.

795
00:54:55,750 --> 00:54:57,249
'You drink too much.

796
00:54:57,249 --> 00:55:01,609
Alcohol is poison for you these days.'

797
00:55:01,609 --> 00:55:04,359
'I've got a headache, Dad,' Dexter said.

798
00:55:04,359 --> 00:55:07,180
'I've been working too hard.

799
00:55:07,180 --> 00:55:09,299
I'm going to lie down for half an hour.

800
00:55:09,299 --> 00:55:10,640
I don't need any food.'

801
00:55:10,640 --> 00:55:16,330
He went upstairs to the room he had slept
in when he was a child.

802
00:55:16,330 --> 00:55:20,950
A few minutes later he was unconscious on
his childhood bed.

803
00:55:20,950 --> 00:55:25,060
It was evening when Dexter woke.

804
00:55:25,060 --> 00:55:27,999
The whole afternoon had passed.

805
00:55:27,999 --> 00:55:31,420
He went to find his father in the kitchen.

806
00:55:31,420 --> 00:55:33,590
'I'm sorry, Dad,' he said.

807
00:55:33,590 --> 00:55:36,160
'I didn't mean to sleep that long.

808
00:55:36,160 --> 00:55:37,740
Why didn't you wake me?'

809
00:55:37,740 --> 00:55:40,099
'It wasn't my job.

810
00:55:40,099 --> 00:55:44,760
You're not a child any longer, Dexter,' his
father replied angrily.

811
00:55:44,760 --> 00:55:48,530
'And you were so drunk, there wasn't any point
in waking you.

812
00:55:48,530 --> 00:55:54,300
You don't think that your mother wanted to
see you like this, do you?'

813
00:55:54,300 --> 00:55:57,160
'I'm sorry,' Dexter said again.

814
00:55:57,160 --> 00:55:58,970
He looked around the room.

815
00:55:58,970 --> 00:56:00,849
'Where did I put my car keys?

816
00:56:00,849 --> 00:56:03,520
I have to go now.'

817
00:56:03,520 --> 00:56:06,690
'I've got them and I'm going to keep them,'
his father replied.

818
00:56:06,690 --> 00:56:09,349
'You must not drive when you're drunk, Dexter.

819
00:56:09,349 --> 00:56:14,249
You'll kill yourself or you'll kill someone
else, which will be worse.

820
00:56:14,249 --> 00:56:16,559
I'll drive you to the station now.

821
00:56:16,559 --> 00:56:19,000
You can get the train back to London.

822
00:56:19,000 --> 00:56:23,900
And you can come and collect your car at the
weekend, if you're sober by then.

823
00:56:23,900 --> 00:56:28,960
Perhaps you'll be able to talk sensibly to
your mother then, too.'

824
00:56:28,960 --> 00:56:32,720
Dexter tried to argue, but his father wouldn't
listen to him.

825
00:56:32,720 --> 00:56:35,270
And he wouldn't talk to him on the way to
the station.

826
00:56:35,270 --> 00:56:41,839
But as Dexter was getting out of the car,
the older man held his arm.

827
00:56:41,839 --> 00:56:46,839
'Listen to me, Dexter,' Stephen Mayhew said
very seriously.

828
00:56:46,839 --> 00:56:51,249
'Your mother was looking forward to your visit
today.

829
00:56:51,249 --> 00:56:53,010
And now she's very upset.

830
00:56:53,010 --> 00:56:57,089
She hasn't long to live, you must know that.

831
00:56:57,089 --> 00:57:01,589
If you come here drunk again, I won't let
you into the house to see her.

832
00:57:01,589 --> 00:57:03,180
Do you understand me?

833
00:57:03,180 --> 00:57:06,400
I won't open the door to you.'

834
00:57:06,400 --> 00:57:11,650
Stephen drove away and Dexter walked sadly
into the station.

835
00:57:11,650 --> 00:57:15,230
When he was waiting for the train he tried
to phone Emma.

836
00:57:15,230 --> 00:57:18,930
'Emma will understand me,' he told himself.

837
00:57:18,930 --> 00:57:21,740
'I need to see Emma.'

838
00:57:21,740 --> 00:57:23,900
But Emma wasn't at home.

839
00:57:23,900 --> 00:57:27,059
He left a message on her answer phone.

840
00:57:27,059 --> 00:57:29,390
He asked if they could meet later that evening.

841
00:57:29,390 --> 00:57:32,710
He said he'd call again.

842
00:57:32,710 --> 00:57:37,859
When he got back to his flat and called again,
Dexter still got the answer phone.

843
00:57:37,859 --> 00:57:41,559
'Emma, where are you?' he said to the machine.

844
00:57:41,559 --> 00:57:43,489
'I miss you.

845
00:57:43,489 --> 00:57:45,390
I need you.

846
00:57:45,390 --> 00:57:48,700
I'll try again later.'

847
00:57:48,700 --> 00:57:52,730
Covent Garden and King's Cross, London.

848
00:57:52,730 --> 00:57:57,849
Emma didn't get any of Dexter's phone messages
that evening because she wasn't at home.

849
00:57:57,849 --> 00:58:04,289
When Dexter left his first message, she had
just left her flat in Earls Court, West London.

850
00:58:04,289 --> 00:58:07,170
She was walking to the nearby Underground
station.

851
00:58:07,170 --> 00:58:12,819
She was on her way to an Italian restaurant
in Covent Garden where she was going to meet

852
00:58:12,819 --> 00:58:15,390
Ian Whitehead.

853
00:58:15,390 --> 00:58:21,910
Emma had only seen Ian a few times since she
had left Loco Caliente to train as a teacher,

854
00:58:21,910 --> 00:58:23,739
but they were still friends.

855
00:58:23,739 --> 00:58:27,220
They sometimes talked on the phone.

856
00:58:27,220 --> 00:58:30,920
And tonight he had invited her to meet him
for dinner.

857
00:58:30,920 --> 00:58:35,289
They had been friends for three years, but
Emma had never slept with Ian.

858
00:58:35,289 --> 00:58:39,460
She knew that he wanted to sleep with her.

859
00:58:39,460 --> 00:58:43,749
She liked him, but did she want to sleep with
him too?

860
00:58:43,749 --> 00:58:49,180
She didn't know and she wondered now how the
evening was going to end.

861
00:58:49,180 --> 00:58:53,150
At the station, Emma bought a ticket and waited
for her train.

862
00:58:53,150 --> 00:58:57,220
Soon, it arrived and Emma boarded it.

863
00:58:57,220 --> 00:59:01,759
She sat and thought about how her life had
changed since she had met Ian.

864
00:59:01,759 --> 00:59:06,680
She no longer shared a flat with Tilly Killick.

865
00:59:06,680 --> 00:59:11,890
Now she lived on her own in the small rented
flat in Earls Court.

866
00:59:11,890 --> 00:59:16,039
And now she was ready for a new career.

867
00:59:16,039 --> 00:59:21,650
Tomorrow she was going to an interview for
a job as a teacher of English and Drama.

868
00:59:21,650 --> 00:59:28,329
The job was in a comprehensive school in Leytonstone,
in a poor part of East London.

869
00:59:28,329 --> 00:59:32,329
Emma was very confident about this job.

870
00:59:32,329 --> 00:59:37,069
She had enjoyed her year at teacher training
college and she knew that she was going to

871
00:59:37,069 --> 00:59:39,390
be a brilliant teacher.

872
00:59:39,390 --> 00:59:42,180
Yes, her life had changed.

873
00:59:42,180 --> 00:59:47,190
But Emma knew that her character had changed
too.

874
00:59:47,190 --> 00:59:48,500
She had mellowed.

875
00:59:48,500 --> 00:59:54,700
She no longer had a strong opinion about everything
that happened in the world.

876
00:59:54,700 --> 00:59:59,710
Sometimes, she could even see that there were
two sides to any argument.

877
00:59:59,710 --> 01:00:05,230
'I'm twenty-seven - perhaps that's the reason,'
she thought.

878
01:00:05,230 --> 01:00:08,539
'Perhaps I'm getting old.

879
01:00:08,539 --> 01:00:11,980
Perhaps I'm ready to compromise.'

880
01:00:11,980 --> 01:00:16,849
When Emma arrived at the restaurant, she saw
that Ian was already there.

881
01:00:16,849 --> 01:00:21,239
She hoped that this was the beginning of a
pleasant evening.

882
01:00:21,239 --> 01:00:25,339
Later, she'd decide about what was going to
happen next.

883
01:00:25,339 --> 01:00:30,619
They ordered food and wine and Ian started
to talk.

884
01:00:30,619 --> 01:00:36,259
He seemed very nervous and Emma tried to help
him to relax.

885
01:00:36,259 --> 01:00:42,269
But an hour later - at about the time Dexter
was leaving his second message on her answer

886
01:00:42,269 --> 01:00:45,660
phone - Emma was feeling desperate.

887
01:00:45,660 --> 01:00:50,049
Ian had been trying much too hard to make
her laugh.

888
01:00:50,049 --> 01:00:54,700
She guessed that he was practising his stand-up
comedy act on her.

889
01:00:54,700 --> 01:01:01,019
The problem was that everything he said was
a joke and it was impossible to have a conversation

890
01:01:01,019 --> 01:01:02,319
with him.

891
01:01:02,319 --> 01:01:05,710
This was driving her crazy.

892
01:01:05,710 --> 01:01:09,529
She guessed that Ian was feeling desperate
too.

893
01:01:09,529 --> 01:01:13,130
Everything he said made the evening worse.

894
01:01:13,130 --> 01:01:16,710
In part of her mind Emma wanted to leave and
go home.

895
01:01:16,710 --> 01:01:22,230
But in another part of her mind she felt terribly
sorry for Ian.

896
01:01:22,230 --> 01:01:28,779
It was clear to her that he wasn't a good
comedian and that his ambition to have a career

897
01:01:28,779 --> 01:01:32,299
in stand-up was just a dream.

898
01:01:32,299 --> 01:01:36,960
At last, she couldn't listen to any more bad
jokes.

899
01:01:36,960 --> 01:01:42,960
'Ian,' she said suddenly, 'will you be quiet
for a minute, please!

900
01:01:42,960 --> 01:01:45,410
Will you just shut up!'

901
01:01:45,410 --> 01:01:50,140
Ian looked very surprised and he stopped talking.

902
01:01:50,140 --> 01:01:58,269
After a few minutes of silence, he asked quietly,
'Do you see your friend Dexter much these

903
01:01:58,269 --> 01:01:59,269
days?'

904
01:01:59,269 --> 01:02:05,240
Emma suddenly understood why Ian had been
so nervous all evening.

905
01:02:05,240 --> 01:02:08,859
'No, we don't meet very often,' she replied.

906
01:02:08,859 --> 01:02:11,749
'But we speak on the phone most days.

907
01:02:11,749 --> 01:02:17,630
He's busy with his TV career and his girlfriends
- you know what Dexter's like.

908
01:02:17,630 --> 01:02:23,079
He's always been a bit crazy and now he's
a bit more crazy, I think.

909
01:02:23,079 --> 01:02:29,230
His mother is seriously ill and he's drinking
far too much.'

910
01:02:29,230 --> 01:02:32,309
'I'm sorry to hear that,' said Ian.

911
01:02:32,309 --> 01:02:38,499
Then, after a pause, he said, 'To be honest
I never liked him much.

912
01:02:38,499 --> 01:02:41,359
I always thought that he took you for granted.'

913
01:02:41,359 --> 01:02:44,989
They were both silent for a few minutes.

914
01:02:44,989 --> 01:02:47,579
Then Ian spoke again.

915
01:02:47,579 --> 01:02:51,140
'Well, we've finished the wine,' he said.

916
01:02:51,140 --> 01:02:53,609
'Shall we have some brandy?'

917
01:02:53,609 --> 01:02:59,900
By the time they left the restaurant, Emma
and Ian were both a bit drunk.

918
01:02:59,900 --> 01:03:04,349
Outside the restaurant, Emma turned to Ian
and kissed him.

919
01:03:04,349 --> 01:03:08,890
She had decided that tonight, she was ready
to compromise.

920
01:03:08,890 --> 01:03:13,479
'Shall I come home with you?'

921
01:03:13,479 --> 01:03:15,460
she asked quietly.

922
01:03:15,460 --> 01:03:20,759
'Emma, that's a lovely idea,' Ian told her.

923
01:03:20,759 --> 01:03:26,960
And when Dexter phoned Emma's number again
at midnight, there still wasn't anyone at

924
01:03:26,960 --> 01:03:27,960
home.

925
01:03:27,960 --> 01:03:34,160
Emma was at Ian Whitehead's and she was going
to stay there until morning.

926
01:03:34,160 --> 01:03:35,900
Dexter was now feeling desperate.

927
01:03:35,900 --> 01:03:38,349
So he called another number.

928
01:03:38,349 --> 01:03:44,430
'Hi, Naomi, this is Dexter,' he said in his
television voice.

929
01:03:44,430 --> 01:03:45,849
'I miss you, girl.

930
01:03:45,849 --> 01:03:47,270
I need you tonight.

931
01:03:47,270 --> 01:04:05,940
Can you find a taxi and come to my flat?

932
