01:35:43,159 --> 01:35:48,389
The River Thames looked lovely on this warm,
sunny afternoon, Emma Morley thought.

1401
01:35:48,389 --> 01:35:52,900
It was a work day, but Emma wasn't at school.

1402
01:35:52,900 --> 01:35:57,719
Teaching had finished for the term but there
was a very important staff meeting happening

1403
01:35:57,719 --> 01:35:59,659
at the school.

1404
01:35:59,659 --> 01:36:03,790
Emma was needed there, but she didn't really
care about that.

1405
01:36:03,790 --> 01:36:09,010
She had phoned the headteacher's secretary
that morning and told her that she was ill

1406
01:36:09,010 --> 01:36:10,860
and had to stay in bed.

1407
01:36:10,860 --> 01:36:13,600
The woman clearly hadn't believed her.

1408
01:36:13,600 --> 01:36:16,790
Emma didn't care about that either.

1409
01:36:16,790 --> 01:36:19,329
Emma wasn't really ill at all.

1410
01:36:19,329 --> 01:36:21,320
In fact, she was feeling good.

1411
01:36:21,320 --> 01:36:25,770
And she had been to a meeting - a meeting
with a publisher.

1412
01:36:25,770 --> 01:36:33,719
At last Emma was feeling confident about something
she had written - a novel for young readers.

1413
01:36:33,719 --> 01:36:37,940
It was about a group of children at an East
London school.

1414
01:36:37,940 --> 01:36:43,790
The children were appearing in a school production
of Oliver! and the story was told by one of

1415
01:36:43,790 --> 01:36:47,050
the actors - a girl called Julie Criscoll.

1416
01:36:47,050 --> 01:36:53,190
Julie was a rude, angry, teenage girl with
a good heart.

1417
01:36:53,190 --> 01:36:56,330
The book was funny and touching.

1418
01:36:56,330 --> 01:37:03,110
Emma had included silly drawings and handwritten
pages in her text, so parts of it looked like

1419
01:37:03,110 --> 01:37:04,909
a schoolgirl's diary.

1420
01:37:04,909 --> 01:37:08,610
She knew that what she had written was really
good.

1421
01:37:08,610 --> 01:37:12,309
And now, other people thought it was good
too.

1422
01:37:12,309 --> 01:37:17,739
Perhaps soon, she was going to be a published
author.

1423
01:37:17,739 --> 01:37:22,699
Emma wanted to write and she wanted even more
to stop teaching.

1424
01:37:22,699 --> 01:37:25,070
She thought every day about resigning.

1425
01:37:25,070 --> 01:37:31,440
Her job at the school had been very difficult
for the last year.

1426
01:37:31,440 --> 01:37:36,420
Phil Godaiming had been angry because she
no longer wanted to sleep with him.

1427
01:37:36,420 --> 01:37:40,980
He'd tried to make her life difficult all
year.

1428
01:37:40,980 --> 01:37:46,190
And now she knew that she could write well,
Emma wanted to spend her life writing.

1429
01:37:46,190 --> 01:37:52,760
At her meeting this morning, she had told
the publisher about her ambitions.

1430
01:37:52,760 --> 01:37:55,119
The publisher had been helpful.

1431
01:37:55,119 --> 01:37:58,369
Emma's life was going to change.

1432
01:37:58,369 --> 01:38:03,400
As she walked by the river, her mobile phone
rang.

1433
01:38:03,400 --> 01:38:06,260
Emma did now have a mobile.

1434
01:38:06,260 --> 01:38:10,070
Dexter had been right after all.

1435
01:38:10,070 --> 01:38:14,280
Phil had given it to her during the months
when they'd been close.

1436
01:38:14,280 --> 01:38:19,739
'I want to be able to hear your voice at any
time,' he'd told her.

1437
01:38:19,739 --> 01:38:26,040
As she took the phone from her handbag, Emma
guessed that it was Phil phoning her now.

1438
01:38:26,040 --> 01:38:27,570
She wasn't wrong.

1439
01:38:27,570 --> 01:38:35,239
'So, you're ill in bed, are you?' he said
in his special loud, angry headteacher's voice.

1440
01:38:35,239 --> 01:38:36,909
'Well, I don't believe it.

1441
01:38:36,909 --> 01:38:39,429
I think you're outside, enjoying the sunshine.

1442
01:38:39,429 --> 01:38:41,230
I can hear the traffic noise.'

1443
01:38:41,230 --> 01:38:46,270
'Don't shout at me, Phil,' Emma said quietly.

1444
01:38:46,270 --> 01:38:50,099
'My name's Mr Godaiming, not Phil,' the man
replied.

1445
01:38:50,099 --> 01:38:53,040
'This is serious, you know that.

1446
01:38:53,040 --> 01:38:56,790
I told you that today's meeting was a very
important one.

1447
01:38:56,790 --> 01:38:59,540
There'll be trouble about this, Emma.

1448
01:38:59,540 --> 01:39:04,860
And if you don't want a relationship with
me, I won't protect you from trouble.

1449
01:39:04,860 --> 01:39:06,309
Your job is in danger.'

1450
01:39:06,309 --> 01:39:11,830
'No, it isn't,' Emma replied, laughing.

1451
01:39:11,830 --> 01:39:14,440
'I'm resigning from my job - now!

1452
01:39:14,440 --> 01:39:17,619
Do you understand?

1453
01:39:17,619 --> 01:39:19,730
I've resigned!

1454
01:39:19,730 --> 01:39:22,909
Goodbye, Mr Godaiming.'

1455
01:39:22,909 --> 01:39:28,050
She switched off her phone and for a moment,
she thought about throwing it into the river.

1456
01:39:28,050 --> 01:39:46,340
But after a few seconds, she put it back in
her bag.

1457
01:39:46,340 --> 01:39:48,940
CHAPTER ELEVEN
Dexter in Love

1458
01:39:48,940 --> 01:39:54,239
Wednesday, 15th July 1998

1459
01:39:54,239 --> 01:39:56,900
Chichester, Sussex

1460
01:39:56,900 --> 01:40:03,540
Dexter Mayhew was lying in bed with Sylvie
Cope at the end of a difficult day.

1461
01:40:03,540 --> 01:40:08,239
Recently, something strange had happened to
Dexter.

1462
01:40:08,239 --> 01:40:10,530
He had fallen in love.

1463
01:40:10,530 --> 01:40:15,670
He'd had many lovers but he'd never been in
love before.

1464
01:40:15,670 --> 01:40:21,400
And now the girl beside him was more important
to him than anything in the world.

1465
01:40:21,400 --> 01:40:25,530
He almost couldn't believe his luck.

1466
01:40:25,530 --> 01:40:33,090
Sylvie was tall, slim and beautiful, with
long, straight hair and a heart-shaped face.

1467
01:40:33,090 --> 01:40:39,969
She and Dexter had known each other for several
months and they spent lots of time together.

1468
01:40:39,969 --> 01:40:46,380
Every weekend they flew to a different European
city and they always had a wonderful time.

1469
01:40:46,380 --> 01:40:50,179
They spent lots of Dexter's money in expensive
shops.

1470
01:40:50,179 --> 01:40:56,820
Sylvie was excited to know Dexter in real
life, after seeing him on television.

1471
01:40:56,820 --> 01:41:01,671
But the truth was that Dexter liked Sylvie
much more than she liked him.

1472
01:41:01,671 --> 01:41:02,671
But Dexter actually enjoyed this.

1473
01:41:02,671 --> 01:41:03,671
It meant that Sylvie was different from his
other girlfriends.

1474
01:41:03,671 --> 01:41:04,671
Sylvie worked in marketing.

1475
01:41:04,671 --> 01:41:05,671
Dexter had met many of her friends, who also
worked in marketing.

1476
01:41:05,671 --> 01:41:06,671
He hadn't liked them and they hadn't liked
him.

1477
01:41:06,671 --> 01:41:07,671
Who cared?

1478
01:41:07,671 --> 01:41:08,671
And tonight, Dexter and Sylvie were staying
at the home of her parents in Chichester.

1479
01:41:08,671 --> 01:41:09,671
Today, Dexter had met the Cope family for
the first time.

1480
01:41:09,671 --> 01:41:10,671
Dexter hadn't enjoyed meeting the Copes much.

1481
01:41:10,671 --> 01:41:11,671
Sylvie's parents clearly didn't admire unimportant
television presenters and Sylvie's twin younger

1482
01:41:11,671 --> 01:41:12,671
brothers had mocked him openly.

1483
01:41:12,671 --> 01:41:13,671
But Dexter really didn't care about that.

1484
01:41:13,671 --> 01:41:14,671
Sylvie was on his side and that was the only
important thing.

1485
01:41:14,671 --> 01:41:15,671
Sylvie was on his side and now she was by
his side, in the big bed.

1486
01:41:15,671 --> 01:41:16,671
'I love you,' Dexter said to her quietly.

1487
01:41:16,671 --> 01:41:17,671
He'd never said these simple words to anyone
before.

1488
01:41:17,671 --> 01:41:18,671
'You're amazing!' he added.

1489
01:41:18,671 --> 01:41:19,671
But Sylvie was already asleep.

1490
01:41:19,671 --> 01:41:20,671
As Dexter lay awake, he realized that he wanted
to tell someone else about Sylvie and about

1491
01:41:20,671 --> 01:41:21,671
his good luck.

1492
01:41:21,671 --> 01:41:22,671
He wanted to tell someone he liked and trusted.

1493
01:41:22,671 --> 01:41:23,671
And suddenly, he knew who he wanted to tell.

1494
01:41:23,671 --> 01:41:24,671
It was someone he hadn't spoken to for three
years.

1495
01:41:24,671 --> 01:41:25,671
He wanted to tell Emma Morley.

1496
01:41:25,671 --> 01:41:26,671
CHAPTER TWELVE
Weddings

1497
01:41:26,671 --> 01:41:27,671
Thursday, 15th July 1999

1498
01:41:27,671 --> 01:41:28,671
Somerset, England

1499
01:41:28,671 --> 01:41:29,671
It seemed to Emma Morley that all her friends
were getting married this year.

1500
01:41:29,671 --> 01:41:30,671
As she drove to Somerset, in the west of England,
on the morning of 15th July, she thought of

1501
01:41:30,671 --> 01:41:31,671
the weddings she had been to recently.

1502
01:41:31,671 --> 01:41:32,671
Some of her friends from university had married
for the first time that year.

1503
01:41:32,671 --> 01:41:33,671
Some of them had married for the second time.

1504
01:41:33,671 --> 01:41:34,671
Watching these wedding ceremonies had made
Emma feel that she was growing old.

1505
01:41:34,671 --> 01:41:35,671
All the university friends she met at them
asked her if she had a boyfriend.

1506
01:41:35,671 --> 01:41:36,671
And they all pretended to be sad for her when
she said she hadn't.

1507
01:41:36,671 --> 01:41:37,671
But they all said she was looking better than
she had ever looked.

1508
01:41:37,671 --> 01:41:38,671
They were right.

1509
01:41:38,671 --> 01:41:39,671
She took better care of herself these days
and she even wore pretty clothes for these

1510
01:41:39,671 --> 01:41:40,671
occasions.

1511
01:41:40,671 --> 01:41:41,671
The best thing about these weddings for Emma
was that she had met Dexter Mayhew at several

1512
01:41:41,671 --> 01:41:42,671
of them.

1513
01:41:42,671 --> 01:41:43,671
At last they were speaking to each other again,
after more than three years of silence.

1514
01:41:43,671 --> 01:41:44,671
That was very, very good.

1515
01:41:44,671 --> 01:41:45,671
Of course, she had met Dexter's girlfriend
Sylvie too and perhaps that was less good.

1516
01:41:45,671 --> 01:41:46,671
But Dexter was clearly in love with the girl,
so Emma tried to be happy for him.

1517
01:41:46,671 --> 01:41:47,671
She had never seen Dexter really in love before.

1518
01:41:47,671 --> 01:41:48,671
This morning, Emma was driving to Somerset
for the marriage of Tilly Killick.

1519
01:41:48,671 --> 01:41:49,671
Tilly was getting married at a posh hotel
in the countryside.

1520
01:41:49,671 --> 01:41:50,671
Dexter had known Tilly during their university
days too, so he was going to be there and

1521
01:41:50,671 --> 01:41:51,671
Emma was looking forward to seeing him again.

1522
01:41:51,671 --> 01:41:52,671
She was driving an old car.

1523
01:41:52,671 --> 01:41:53,671
It was the first car she had ever owned and
it was the best she was able to afford.

1524
01:41:53,671 --> 01:41:54,671
Emma certainly wasn't a rich woman.

1525
01:41:54,671 --> 01:41:55,671
In fact, she was now living on a small advance
from a publisher and was writing her second

1526
01:41:55,671 --> 01:41:56,671
book about Julie Criscoll.

1527
01:41:56,671 --> 01:41:57,671
But the first book was going to be published
soon and the publisher expected it to sell

1528
01:41:57,671 --> 01:41:58,671
very well.

1529
01:41:58,671 --> 01:41:59,671
Emma had some problems with her car during
the journey and she was a bit late when she

1530
01:41:59,671 --> 01:42:00,671
arrived at the hotel.

1531
01:42:00,671 --> 01:42:01,671
The ceremony had already begun when she entered
the big marriage room, so she found a seat

1532
01:42:01,671 --> 01:42:02,671
at the back of the room.

1533
01:42:02,671 --> 01:42:03,671
As she was sitting down, Dexter Mayhew turned
round and saw her.

1534
01:42:03,671 --> 01:42:04,671
He smiled and waved his hand.

1535
01:42:04,671 --> 01:42:05,671
Dexter was sitting at the front with Sylvie.

1536
01:42:05,671 --> 01:42:06,671
He hadn't really been listening to the ceremony.

1537
01:42:06,671 --> 01:42:07,671
He had been counting the number of women in
the room he had slept with.

1538
01:42:07,671 --> 01:42:08,671
'It's five,' he thought.

1539
01:42:08,671 --> 01:42:09,671
'It's five in one room, including the bride.

1540
01:42:09,671 --> 01:42:10,671
It's a good score.

1541
01:42:10,671 --> 01:42:11,671
Is it a record?

1542
01:42:11,671 --> 01:42:12,671
Do I get an extra point for the bride?

1543
01:42:12,671 --> 01:42:13,671
And really, it's five-and-a-half if I count
that night with Emma.'

1544
01:42:13,671 --> 01:42:14,671
And as he thought this, he realized that it
was a bad thing to think.

1545
01:42:14,671 --> 01:42:15,671
He also realized that he wanted to talk to
Emma very much.

1546
01:42:15,671 --> 01:42:16,671
'I'll try to talk to her alone,' he thought.

1547
01:42:16,671 --> 01:42:17,671
'I need to tell her everything.'

1548
01:42:17,671 --> 01:42:18,671
After the ceremony, the party began.

1549
01:42:18,671 --> 01:42:19,671
Dexter left Sylvie with some friends and started
to look for Emma.

1550
01:42:19,671 --> 01:42:20,671
But the first person he met was Callum O'Neill.

1551
01:42:20,671 --> 01:42:21,671
The two men hadn't spoken for a long time.

1552
01:42:21,671 --> 01:42:22,671
Dexter had heard that Callum had sold his
computer business for a huge amount of money.

1553
01:42:22,671 --> 01:42:23,671
He had now started a new business - a successful
chain of sandwich shops.

1554
01:42:23,671 --> 01:42:24,671
Today, he was very expensively dressed in
beautiful, fashionable clothes.

1555
01:42:24,671 --> 01:42:25,671
Dexter remembered that at Edinburgh University,
Callum had worn the same pair of trousers

1556
01:42:25,671 --> 01:42:26,671
every day for three years.

1557
01:42:26,671 --> 01:42:27,671
How things had changed!

1558
01:42:27,671 --> 01:42:28,671
Callum had gone up in the world and Dexter
had come down.

1559
01:42:28,671 --> 01:42:29,671
'Dexter, old friend, you're still alive,'
Callum said.

1560
01:42:29,671 --> 01:42:30,671
'It's been a long time since I've seen you.

1561
01:42:30,671 --> 01:42:31,671
I stopped phoning you because you never returned
my calls.'

1562
01:42:31,671 --> 01:42:32,671
'Didn't I?'

1563
01:42:32,671 --> 01:42:33,671
Dexter said.

1564
01:42:33,671 --> 01:42:34,671
'Well, you know, I've been very busy with
my television programmes.'

1565
01:42:34,671 --> 01:42:35,671
He tried to sound confident.

1566
01:42:35,671 --> 01:42:36,671
'And are you still on television?

1567
01:42:36,671 --> 01:42:37,671
I haven't seen you on TV for a long time,'
Callum said.

1568
01:42:37,671 --> 01:42:38,671
'I'm usually in programmes for sophisticated,
late-night viewers,' Dexter said uncomfortably.

1569
01:42:38,671 --> 01:42:39,671
'Mm.

1570
01:42:39,671 --> 01:42:40,671
Perhaps you need a new career opportunity,'
Callum said.

1571
01:42:40,671 --> 01:42:41,671
'You could work for me, Dex.

1572
01:42:41,671 --> 01:42:42,671
I need a new manager.

1573
01:42:42,671 --> 01:42:43,671
Come and see me soon.

1574
01:42:43,671 --> 01:42:44,671
I'll buy you a good lunch - not sandwiches.

1575
01:42:44,671 --> 01:42:45,671
We'll talk about it.

1576
01:42:45,671 --> 01:42:46,671
Now, let's go and find your lovely girlfriend.

1577
01:42:46,671 --> 01:42:47,671
I saw you with her earlier and I want to meet
her.

1578
01:42:47,671 --> 01:42:48,671
Have you seen my girlfriend?

1579
01:42:48,671 --> 01:42:49,671
I won't ask you to meet her, I'm getting rid
of her soon.'

1580
01:42:49,671 --> 01:42:50,671
Much later in the afternoon, Dexter finally
met up with Emma.

1581
01:42:50,671 --> 01:42:51,671
'Let's go somewhere quiet,' he said.

1582
01:42:51,671 --> 01:42:52,671
'I want to talk to you.'

1583
01:42:52,671 --> 01:42:53,671
'Where's somewhere quiet?'

1584
01:42:53,671 --> 01:42:54,671
Emma asked him.

1585
01:42:54,671 --> 01:42:55,671
'Well, there's a maze here, I believe,' said
Dexter.

1586
01:42:55,671 --> 01:42:56,671
'It's a large one.

1587
01:42:56,671 --> 01:42:57,671
It would be nice to get lost in it.'

1588
01:42:57,671 --> 01:42:58,671
They found the entrance to the maze and they
walked inside.

1589
01:42:58,671 --> 01:42:59,671
They didn't stop until they reached the centre.

1590
01:42:59,671 --> 01:43:00,671
Then they turned to face each other.

1591
01:43:00,671 --> 01:43:01,671
'Well, isn't it strange?'

1592
01:43:01,671 --> 01:43:02,671
Emma began.

1593
01:43:02,671 --> 01:43:03,671
'These days, we only talk at other people's
weddings.'

1594
01:43:03,671 --> 01:43:04,671
'I'm sorry that I've been so obnoxious during
these last few years,' Dexter said quietly.

1595
01:43:04,671 --> 01:43:05,671
'I don't blame you for ending our friendship.

1596
01:43:05,671 --> 01:43:06,671
But I want us to be friends again now.'

1597
01:43:06,671 --> 01:43:07,671
'I'm sorry too, Dex,' Emma replied.

1598
01:43:07,671 --> 01:43:08,671
'Perhaps I didn't understand how badly your
mother's death had hurt you.

1599
01:43:08,671 --> 01:43:09,671
I didn't wait for you to start feeling better.

1600
01:43:09,671 --> 01:43:10,671
We were both to blame.'

1601
01:43:10,671 --> 01:43:11,671
'I'm a different person now, Em,' Dexter said.

1602
01:43:11,671 --> 01:43:12,671
'Sylvie has changed me.

1603
01:43:12,671 --> 01:43:13,671
I love her very much.'

1604
01:43:13,671 --> 01:43:14,671
He stopped speaking for a moment.

1605
01:43:14,671 --> 01:43:15,671
'Emma, there's going to be another wedding
soon,' he went on.

1606
01:43:15,671 --> 01:43:16,671
'Sylvie and I are going to get married later
this year.

1607
01:43:16,671 --> 01:43:17,671
And Sylvie is going to have a baby.'

1608
01:43:17,671 --> 01:43:18,671
For another moment they didn't speak, but
their faces showed their real feelings.

1609
01:43:18,671 --> 01:43:19,671
Then Emma knew that she had to say something
to hide her fee lings, at least.

1610
01:43:19,671 --> 01:43:20,671
'She's a lovely girl, Dex,' Emma said.

1611
01:43:20,671 --> 01:43:21,671
'It's marvellous news.'

1612
01:43:21,671 --> 01:43:22,671
'I think that fatherhood will transform my
life,' Dexter replied.

1613
01:43:22,671 --> 01:43:23,671
'I've almost stopped drinking already.

1614
01:43:23,671 --> 01:43:24,671
I'll be a good family man.'

1615
01:43:24,671 --> 01:43:25,671
'Well, that's good,' said Emma.

1616
01:43:25,671 --> 01:43:26,671
She laughed.

1617
01:43:26,671 --> 01:43:27,671
'Of course, you've just ruined any chance
of future happiness for me, but it's all great

1618
01:43:27,671 --> 01:43:28,671
news.'

1619
01:43:28,671 --> 01:43:29,671
She stopped for a moment.

1620
01:43:29,671 --> 01:43:30,671
'Don't worry,' she added.

1621
01:43:30,671 --> 01:43:31,671
'I'm only joking.'

1622
01:43:31,671 --> 01:43:32,671
And then they both laughed.

1623
01:43:32,671 --> 01:43:33,671
'The wedding will be in September,' said Dexter.

1624
01:43:33,671 --> 01:43:34,671
'Emma, will you help me write my speech for
the big day?'

1625
01:43:34,671 --> 01:43:35,671
'No, Dexter,' said Emma.

1626
01:43:35,671 --> 01:43:36,671
'Don't be an idiot.

1627
01:43:36,671 --> 01:43:37,671
Just look into your heart and write.'

1628
01:43:37,671 --> 01:43:38,671
Then they walked back towards the entrance
of the maze.

