01:53:20,671 --> 01:53:21,671
He was wearing expensive shoes and he didn't
want to ruin them.

2212
01:53:21,671 --> 01:53:22,671
'I don't climb mountains, Em,' he said.

2213
01:53:22,671 --> 01:53:23,671
'I'm not that kind of person.'

2214
01:53:23,671 --> 01:53:24,671
'Dexter, it's only a hill, it's not K2,' Emma
replied, laughing.

2215
01:53:24,671 --> 01:53:25,671
So they climbed Arthur's Seat and when they
reached the top they decided that it wasn't

2216
01:53:25,671 --> 01:53:26,671
really romantic.

2217
01:53:26,671 --> 01:53:27,671
There were too many people already there for
that.

2218
01:53:27,671 --> 01:53:28,671
But Dexter had never climbed the hill before
and he was surprised.

2219
01:53:28,671 --> 01:53:29,671
He enjoyed the view.

2220
01:53:29,671 --> 01:53:30,671
It made an impression on him.

2221
01:53:30,671 --> 01:53:31,671
This didn't often happen.

2222
01:53:31,671 --> 01:53:32,671
'I've lived in this city for four years,'
he said.

2223
01:53:32,671 --> 01:53:33,671
'Now this is my last day in Edinburgh.

2224
01:53:33,671 --> 01:53:34,671
Why haven't I been up here before?'

2225
01:53:34,671 --> 01:53:35,671
'Because you're not that kind of person,'
Emma replied.

2226
01:53:35,671 --> 01:53:36,671
They ate their picnic and then they sat quietly
together.

2227
01:53:36,671 --> 01:53:37,671
'Dexter,' Emma said after a few minutes, 'I
want to say something.

2228
01:53:37,671 --> 01:53:38,671
It's about last night.

2229
01:53:38,671 --> 01:53:39,671
I haven't done that kind of thing often and
I know that you were a bit drunk.

2230
01:53:39,671 --> 01:53:40,671
I know it was just one night, and that's it.

2231
01:53:40,671 --> 01:53:41,671
But I want to say that it was nice for me.

2232
01:53:41,671 --> 01:53:42,671
It was nice and you're nice, Dexter.

2233
01:53:42,671 --> 01:53:43,671
You're a nice person when you allow yourself
to be nice.

2234
01:53:43,671 --> 01:53:44,671
I really like you.'

2235
01:53:44,671 --> 01:53:45,671
Later, on their way back to the bottom of
the hill, they stopped to take some photos.

2236
01:53:45,671 --> 01:53:46,671
Someone took a photo of both of them together.

2237
01:53:46,671 --> 01:53:47,671
Then Emma walked with Dexter back to his flat.

2238
01:53:47,671 --> 01:53:48,671
They found Dexter's parents waiting for him
there.

2239
01:53:48,671 --> 01:53:49,671
'This is my friend Emma Morley,' Dexter told
his parents.

2240
01:53:49,671 --> 01:53:50,671
'Hello Emma, I'm Alison,' Dexter's mother
said.

2241
01:53:50,671 --> 01:53:51,671
'We're pleased to meet you.

2242
01:53:51,671 --> 01:53:52,671
Do you want to come for a drink with us?'

2243
01:53:52,671 --> 01:53:53,671
Emma looked at Dexter.

2244
01:53:53,671 --> 01:53:54,671
He looked unhappy and worried.

2245
01:53:54,671 --> 01:53:55,671
She made a quick decision.

2246
01:53:55,671 --> 01:53:56,671
'No, thank you,' she replied.

2247
01:53:56,671 --> 01:53:57,671
'That's very kind of you, but I have to get
back to my flat.'

2248
01:53:57,671 --> 01:53:58,671
Then she spoke to the boy.

2249
01:53:58,671 --> 01:53:59,671
'Have a nice life, Dexter,' she said quickly.

2250
01:53:59,671 --> 01:54:00,671
She turned and walked away.

2251
01:54:00,671 --> 01:54:01,671
'I'll probably never see him again,' she told
herself as she walked sadly along the street.

2252
01:54:01,671 --> 01:54:02,671
But a few minutes later, as she walked through
the city centre, she heard someone call her

2253
01:54:02,671 --> 01:54:03,671
name behind her.

2254
01:54:03,671 --> 01:54:04,671
She turned and saw Dexter.

2255
01:54:04,671 --> 01:54:05,671
He had been running and he was exhausted".

2256
01:54:05,671 --> 01:54:06,671
'My parents came early,' he said.

2257
01:54:06,671 --> 01:54:07,671
'I didn't have time to get your address and
phone number.'

2258
01:54:07,671 --> 01:54:08,671
Quickly, Emma wrote these on a piece of paper
and Dexter wrote his address and phone number

2259
01:54:08,671 --> 01:54:09,671
for her.

2260
01:54:09,671 --> 01:54:10,671
'Call me when I get back from France,' he
said.

2261
01:54:10,671 --> 01:54:11,671
'Come and stay with us for a few days.

2262
01:54:11,671 --> 01:54:12,671
I want to see you again.'

2263
01:54:12,671 --> 01:54:13,671
Then he kissed her gently and she kissed him.

2264
01:54:13,671 --> 01:54:14,671
They stood in the middle of the busy street
and people on their way home hurried around

2265
01:54:14,671 --> 01:54:15,671
them.

2266
01:54:15,671 --> 01:54:16,671
It was the sweetest kiss either of them ever
knew.

2267
01:54:16,671 --> 01:54:17,671
'Goodbye, Dex,' Emma said.

2268
01:54:17,671 --> 01:54:18,671
'Goodbye.'

2269
01:54:18,671 --> 01:54:19,671
'Goodbye.

2270
01:54:19,671 --> 01:54:20,671
Goodbye.'

